animal.description: Eli is a sweet boy who has quickly adjusted to life in a new foster home. While he is still a big puppy at heart, he has been adjusting to living inside a house and is doing great. He is doing very well with his house training and generally has good manners inside. He likes to walk on a leash and enjoys lounging outside on the deck, preferably with a nice bone to snack on. At some point in Eli’s past, he developed a fear of other dogs and so does need a home where he won’t have that exposure and  be the only pet in a home with a fenced-in yard.  In fact, a fenced yard is required to adopt Eli.  He couldn’t be sweeter with people - whether they are big people (adults) or older children).  He should probably not go into a home with kids under 8. Eli is super smart, a quick learner, and very eager to please. Once he gets to know you, he won’t want to leave your side unless it’s time to hide a bone or play with a toy. He is ready to thrive in a forever home as a great family companion.

animal.description:
Breed:  Chihuahua mix
Age:  3 yrs.
Weight:  14 lbs.
Good with dogs:  yes
Good with cats:  unsure
Good with kids:  no
Energy level:  unsure
Good with men/strangers:  yes
Hypoallergenic:  no

Special home requirements or medical:  adult only home; needs a yard
Additional info:

Maple has made a lot of progress in the few months that she has been with us and now that she has come out of her shell we have learned a lot more about what she needs. Maple is a very special girl and what her new family is going to have to understand is that she's not going to instantly love you and jump into your laps for kisses, because she still has trust issues it takes her time to get used to people. She is a sweet and lovable girl, but there won't be any instant love connection from her, the reward will come later. Maple does adore other dogs and bonds so much quicker to them than humans, so Maple is perfect for someone that is looking for a companion for their dog and is ok with her needing some time to come around. She has also now learned to walk on a leash, although a bit nervous still this is a work in progress and she does have a curious nature so I'm sure with time she will become more confident on her walks.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG, PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU HAVE READ THE DOG'S INFORMATION CAREFULLY.  ONCE YOU HAVE DONE SO, PLEASE DO THE FOLLOWING:
1.       Visit www.dogswithoutborders.org
2.      Then fill out an online ADOPTION APPLICATION -  http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-application/
3.       Please wait to hear from our representative in approximately 48 hours on weekdays.
4.       To learn more about our adoption process, please look up our Adoption FAQ’s. - http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-faq/

animal.description:
MEET >>>Banditas!! **Please Note: This is a courtesy post for another rescue; different adoption fees/policy apply.

>>>Oh so sweet and beautiful Banditas is back in Phoenix. She is the kissing bandit. She loves to give kisses if you allow her to! Many people wanted to meet her, but she was a couple hours away so we brought her back here. She has been in boarding for over a year. This beautiful kissing gal stole my heart over a year ago. Bandita is definitely an alpha female that needs a firm handler. She does mind well though. She is so sweet, she loves to kiss, but only if you want to! She knows sit, and down. She is also kennel trained. She has done well with male dogs her size. I would recommend only one male dog or her as an only pup. She has plenty of love to give! Bandita should be with kids over 12+. She is potty trained too! This kissing gal loves everyone she meets. She needs a home with a yard. PLEASE CALL 520-800-4633 ASK FOR Terri Boarder. Remember my name Kissing Banditas! I'm in Phoenix waiting for you! Hurry up, I don't really like the boarding place where i'm at, too much noise and too many dogs. I was hurting myself the other day, so I need out quick.....Please call asap!

For more information or to meet this pet, please complete an application or send email to info@underdogaz.com

If you're reading this via a pet-search site, please view this pet's page

animal.description:
Millie is a complete sweetheart. We took her in after she was posted on Facebook heavily pregnant with a broken leg. She went into labor during transport to get to us. She had a beautiful litter of puppies & was a wonderful mother! Unfortunately, her leg isn't able to be saved & is scheduled to be amputated. We don't think it'll slow her down at all! This sweet girl deserves an amazing life after everything she's been through! We're so glad that we were alerted to her & were able to take her in! She's a special girl & will make an amazing companion.

Hi my name is Sarina!

I’m an older Staffordshire Terrier that came from a horrible situation in July 2019.  I’m finally healthy. I have lots of scarring and my teats from having so many liters of puppies have never shrunk back down.

I came from a fighting ring and was over used for breeding and when I got older, they decided to use me as bait.  I’m not the prettiest gal in the bunch, but my heart is huge and I’m so loving and trusting!  

I love kids, but have not been around many except my foster mama's grandkids who are 3 and 5 years old.  I love my kennel buddy Ceasar.  He keeps me company!  I love, LOVE walks.  I was chained to a tree until I came here and I get to walk the neighborhood everyday now!  I will need lots of patience as I’ve never been in a real home before

Please contact Top RJs and set up a meet and greet.  You won’t be sorry!

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO ON THIS DOG BEFORE REQUESTING AN APPLICATION.  MANY OF OUR DOGS HAVE STRICT REQUIREMENTS FOR THEIR ADOPTION.

Shorty is a 5 year old male Chihuahua, about 10 pounds. Shorty and Tinker came into rescue together when their owner passed away. While they lived together, Shorty was ruling the partnership, being overly protective and did not allow Tinker to thrive. They now live in separate foster homes and are doing fantastic apart. Hi there, my name is Shorty. I am somewhat of a mutt but have been found to look similar to a chihuahua. Also, I have a cute little curly tail so I think I might be a part pug also. I was recently separated from my brother Tinker and while I liked bossing him around, I feel I am doing just fine without him. I would not mind having another dog to live with. I am fairly young and love to play, eat, and run around in the backyard. I love going outside and barking at all the people and birds that fly around. It’s one of my favorite things to do along with walks. I have found that some of my foster siblings hate rain but I find it so refreshing. I feel that I would do best in a home with no children as I am protective of my personal space. I am willing to nip if I am scared. As you know I did live in a home where my male owner died so I tend to sometimes be more friendly to men than women. I am a man's man, so to speak! Overall I do consider myself to be a fun and happy dog that can also be very playful. I would love to find out if you might be my forever home. Owner surrender

Adoption contract and fee applies.  All adoptable dogs can be met at adoption events hosted every weekend. For a list of scheduled events go to: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/events .  Smidget Rescue is not a shelter, and dogs cannot be seen at the Rescue location. All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums.   All adoptable dogs are spayed or neutered at 6 months of age or older, and always before being placed in their new homes.  APPLICATIONS CAN BE OBTAINED BY EMAIL ONLY. Adoption process includes application, meet & greet, home visit and reference check. Email Jamie at smidgetrescue@hotmail.com or click on the CONTACT link on this page.   Notice:  We do not ship dogs out of state.  If you live within a five-hour radius of Seattle, WA, (such as Portland, Vancouver B.C., etc.), we can arrange for a home visit.  If your home seems like a great fit for the dog you would like to adopt, you must then drive to meet the dog at one of our weekend events or at the fosters home.

animal.description:
Okay ladies and gentlemen if you are looking for an awesome hiking buddy and ball player then look no further. Let me introduce myself, my name is Mary Belle and I am an approximately 2 year old tri color Catahoula Curr Mix and about 45lbs. I love to go on adventures and playing ball in the yard.
If you are interested in adopting me, I need to be the only fur child of any kind in the house or outside. I mean who really needs friends when we have each other. Also kids, I would prefer them in there teens and to be very dog savvy. I do have a few quirks that I’m hoping you could look past and help me work on them to make me the best dog possible. I prefer not to be picked up, or restrained. If you do I may nip you, and that’s only because I didn’t have the greatest upbringing before I came to CAFA. Also when we first meet I may be a little shy, but give it some time and I will warm right up and be your pal. Also in July of 2020 I had to undergo the dreaded heart worm treatment that a lot of us end up having to thru down south. But I have been given the green light and am now looking for my forever after. So please if you are interested in meeting me click that button that says ask about Mary Belle and someone will get back to you. Don’t worry I’m not going anywhere since I want my forever home too.

Adoption fees details: 
Puppies - Adults $ 550, Seniors $375. These adoption rates include transport from Alexandria, Louisiana to designated New England adopter pick up locations and NE foster homes using either Rescue Road Trips, Pets LLC or CAFA Transport. If you do a search you will see that this is a very reasonable adoption fee and comparable to other rescues. Adoption fee breakdown:Adoption Fee:   $  365.00Transportation Fee:  $ 185.00MA and NH only--Quarantine fee if applicable:  $125.00

Medical details:
All our dogs are altered (spayed or neutered), DHLPP, rabies, Bordetella, Heartworm tested with negative test results, microchipped, treated for parasites and on monthly heartworm and flea and tick prevention. A health certificate is issued by a licensed Louisiana veterinarian.

Adoption details:  
In some instances, a meet and greet is not possible before adoption unless we have a foster home in New England available. Available for a Meeting confirms the dog is in a NE Foster home and available for a meeting in the city state provided.  Most times our dogs get adopted before a foster home becomes available - and if so, they go straight to adopters home. Foster parents talk to adopters and feel confident that this will be a match before our dogs are transported up. Also if by some chance it is not a match we have a safety net in place as we ask that adopters to let us know that it is not a match and we direct you to take the dog to a foster home or boarding kennel once that is arranged. If necessary, we will ask you to foster the dog until a foster home can be arranged. 
Transport details:Rescue Road Trips (rescueroadtrips.com), Pets LLC (petsllc.net) or CAFA Transport will deliver our precious pups on commercial rescue animal transport to designated locations.  The fee is 185.00 which IS INCLUDED in your adoption fee already.**Rescue Road Trips, was featured on The Today Show - view it at http://www.today.com/video/today/55034556#55034556

MA and NH RESIDENTS:
If you are a Massachusetts or New Hampshire residence, an additional fee of $125.00 will apply due to State quarantine fee requirements. If the dog is in a foster home in MA or NH, this fee will be added in the adoption fee regardless of where the adopters home is located making the total adoption fee $675.00 for puppies and adults $495.00 for Seniors, otherwise the full adoption fee for all other states is $550.00 for puppies and adults and $375.00 for seniors. This includes a 48 quarantine, recheck by a MA licensed veterinarian, and issued a MA health certificate.

Visit all our available dogs at www.cenlaallianceforanimals.comWe update and add dogs frequently.

We hope to help make a difference in a rescue dogs life into loving responsible homes.

Cookie is a 4 year old Border Collie mix. She is shy and skittish when she meets new people. When she has warmed up to people, she is affectionate and likes to be around them. She is good with other dogs after a proper introduction is done. Unfortunately we do not know how she is with cats. Cookie's forever home is required to have a PRIVACY fenced yard where she can safely run and play. She can jump over a chain link fence. NO CHILDREN. Cookie is spayed, up to date on her vaccinations, on monthly heartworm preventative as well as house and crate trained. Cookie will be a great furry family member for a very lucky family!!!

All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. A home visit is required to ensure our dog is going to a safe environment and our dog gets along with your dog(s) and/or cat(s). We require all our dogs over the age of 1 year attend 1 obedience class (6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. No out of state or out of the U.S. adoptions or fosters. Cookie's adoption fee is $275.

animal.description:
Max is a senior now at around 10 years old and is now looking for his forever home. Max has always been overlooked as he is a lab mix and because of his black colouring most people will overlook a good boy like this. Max has had no easy road and although it is not one of those sad stories you always see it really is a sad story. Through no ones fault months and years past for Max as he had no interest in him at all. The rescue is currently seeking a foster or an adopter as Max needs somewhere to call home or a place to rest his head. Although at his age he should be slow he is not. He is spry and loves to interact. A home with older children over the age of 12, for no other reason than his age and fast rapid movements. 

Max is fully vetted, housebroken and crate trained.  He is capable and needing of smiles, affection, and love, but he doesn't just give his heart away quickly and with abandon. Who can blame him?!!!  If you understand there is a story behind the soulful eyes and you give him some time and space, Max will let you in. Believe me, when this boy loves you, he loves you forever, and it's all worth it!! He is laid back but still loves a good play session, and boy does he love toys and treats!!! He is an amazing companion, a great listener and will be your best friend!

He's getting older and we need to make his golden years his best years!! His ideal home would be an experienced, adult only home where he is the only pet. We really want him to have it all and he deserves to be your one and only!!! A back yard would be amazing (but not required) since he does like to relive his lost puppy years and run around every now and then.

Email harescue1@aol.com to inquire

He would do well with older kids. He always wants to play with older kids, but he is nervous around young children.

We take turns going to adoption shows to find our forever families on Thursday from 6:00-8:30 at PetSmart in Montgomery Plaza (415 Carroll St, Fort Worth, TX 76107). If you're interested in me, please contact my rescue family at GNARanimalrescue@gmail to make sure they bring me to meet you!

animal.description:
Rogue 3 1/2 year old black female with natural ears. She has been spayed and gastropexied. Rogue has come back to rescue through no fault of her own, as her family is splitting up and she had nowhere to go. She has lived with other dogs, so she could be placed with another dog, but it would need to be a large dog as she has a strong prey drive. If she is placed with a home with children, they would need to be older children. Due to her prey drive, living with cats would not be recommended. She takes a bit of time to warm up to strangers and even longer to men. She is highly food motivated and will learn your routine quickly with the help of tasty treats. Once she is comfortable with you, she loves coming to you to get rubs and scratches. Rogue is crate trained and walks nicely on the leash. Rogue does guard her food from other dogs so we would need an experienced Dane owner to take this sweet girl on. When she is given time, she is does not hesitate to show you what a great dog she is. One of her favorite things to do is to play fetch so if you want an active dog to be active with, she is your girl! Rogue came to MAGDRL in December 2019. (2)



For more info on this dog and our adoption policies, visit PA MAGDRL at http://www.padanerescue.com. MAGDRL adopts Great Danes in NY, NJ, PA, MD, DE, DC, VA, & WV.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi! I'm Sammy and I'm pictured with my sister Jazzy. I'm Sammy, a fun-loving 13 year old boy who is excited to find his fur-ever home!! Our owner was sick and couldn't take care of us anymore so now we need a new forever home. My sister Jazzy is in kidney failure so even though we have been together a long time, I will need to learn to live without her- that's why it would be great to find a home since I'm loosing my sister! Foster Mom says we're some of the sweetest dogs you'll ever meet!

Even though I am getting on in age, and can be lazy, I still love to be around our people, including children - in fact my job is to protect them kiddos! I love to ride in the car and to sleep with foster mom, usually under the covers. I love to lay on the sofa, close to people too. i especially love to be petted, but we don't love being held.

While I like to walk with a harnesses, I don't always do well with other dogs. When our foster family isn't home I stay in a crate together with my sister Jazzy. When they come home they take us out, and take us out often when they're here with us. Since we are older we'll occassionally have an accident if you don't notice us telling you we need to go outside.

We love food and treats! I don't have too many teeth left but that never lets that stop me!

No cats for me, please!

I think you'll see I'd be great additions to a family who wants to love and snuggle and be loved back, unconditionally. Please adopt me today!

animal.description:
Tommy Bahama is a sweet, happy, energetic young dog who came to FUR during one of our Bahamas rescue missions after Hurricane Dorian. He was badly injured, with two broken legs and a dislocated hip, but he has recovered from surgery and he's now officially adoptable. He absolutely needs a fenced in yard to run, and he would do best with a younger, playful dog. He loves all dogs, but he's a little too much for seniors or little dogs. 
 
Tommy's a super sweet, happy, affectionate boy who loves to run and play.  He's very smart, food motivated, and eager to please. He also loves to cuddle.  He has never had an accident in the house. He will bark and let you know when he has to go outside. 

At only a year and a half old, he's a big puppy at heart.  He is an amazing dog and he will make a someone very happy!  No cats, please. We think he'd be fine with older kids, but he might knock small children over. 

Our adoption fee is $150, including neuter, microchip, and vaccinations up to date as of the day he goes home. 

If you're interested, you can submit an adoption application here:
https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/FUR/Dog
animal.name: Tommy Bahama

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
My name is Alvin, If you are looking for a buddy to snuggle on the couch with, I am your guy! I also like to play with squeaky toys and soccer balls. I came from Arkansas back in the day, where I had a rough start and I sometimes am selective of my dog friends. After a proper introduction with new dogs though, I love to play with them.

Not to brag, but I am really smart, too! I have completed obedience 1 class and know a lot of verbal commands and I'm eager to learn more!! I like to make my people happy and smile, I'll smile back! I am very food motivated, so if you want to teach me even more it won't be hard! I Love my food puzzle and keeping my mind and body active. I'd be the best co-pilot in the car! I am also kennel trained and have learned how to walk with a gentle leader so I don't pull so much. And yes, I'm house trained, what do you think I am an animal?! I do not like cats and get very nervous around children so I would do best in a home without either. Looking for a mature home that has had some dog experience. I wouldn't mind being the only dog so I can get lots of love and attention, but I would also be happy with another doggy friend as long as we are a good fit. I'm eagerly waiting for someone to please!

Alvin's adoption fee is $250 and includes his neuter, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives. Last Hope requires that all animals be kept as indoor pets only, altered and current on vaccinations and preventatives. Our adoption process includes reference and background checks, a vet check and a home visit.
animal.name: Alvin

animal.description:
Hobbes is a handsome, sweet, ultra-playful and fun 18-month-old, 50-pound male brindle and white pit bull/boxer-mix looking for a loving guardian. 

Hobbes sits when asked, but he does excitedly jump up on people. His tail is always happily wagging.

This fun boy came to Chicago from Metropolis, Illinois where he was found stray. 

He loves to play ball and may be best with teens and adults due to his high-energy level.

He is good with all other dogs and but he has not been cat-tested. 

Hobbes is very healthy, neutered, up-to-date on vaccines, microchipped, heartworm and fecal-tested negative.

To meet and possibly adopt Hobbes, please contact Melia at melia88@comcast.net or 708-224-1900 for an adoption application.

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
COURTESY POST ONLY- RAKSHA is in CALIFORNIA USA and has not been evaluated by our rescue. Owner willing to travel if right home is found. Our rescue is just trying to help Raksha find a home. 

Raksha is a 100lb, 4-year old Tosa Inu Mastiff originally rescued from a meat farm in South Korea. Despite having a very traumatic beginning to her life, she is a loving, playful, and goofy dog that enjoys cuddling with her humans, hiking, and playing with her toys. 

 Raksha currently lives with another dog and two cats. She has expressed some dog aggression issues (particularly under high-anxiety situations), and due to this she would be best in a home without other animals and with sufficient outdoor space to explore. 

She is great with humans, including children, but due to her size it is recommended that she not live with young children. The ideal situation for Raksha would be in a country setting with a human who enjoys long walks/hikes (which help to reduce Raksha's general anxiety) and who is a confident leader capable of devoting time and energy to continuing to train/lead Raksha to be comfortable in the world. 

She is spayed, micro-chipped, and up to date on all vaccinations. I have complete medical records for her.

She is crate-trained, walks really well on a leash, and has recently been trained using a muzzle for small periods of time (on walks, when other dogs are around, etc

***Please consider the following before application: not good with other dogs, must be re-homed in a home without other pets or small children.

animal.description:
Following is a list of our sanctuary dogs with brief descriptions. We try to evaluate each new rescue carefully in regard to temperament and the reality is that sometimes we get a dog that displays behaviors we can manage here at the rescue but that we are not comfortable placing with most or any adopters. These behaviors usually involve their guardian breed characteristics and a lack of proper socialization and experiences when younger but can also just be their genetic personality and temperament. Being in a more rural and controlled situation here at the rescue, rather than in a busy and /or neighborhood environment, we can insure a consistent routine and monitor everyone closely. 
We work to insure all the sanctuary dogs have the best quality life possible. They have heated and air conditioned large inside kennels with Kuranda beds, outside runs and a 4 acre yard to play in, patrol and guard. We also integrate inside the house time into their routines as space and personalities permit but they still require their kennel space part of the time and in certain situations. The dogs are matched up in compatible play pairs or groups based on their personality so they have friends to play and patrol the yard with. All of our sanctuary rescues are fully vetted and kept up to date on any and all needed vet care as well as groomed regularly and worked with on training and manners. And very importantly, they are much loved, flaws and all. Please consider helping to sponsor the care of one of our sanctuary rescues. Contributions toward the care of the dogs at the rescue are helpful and greatly appreciated as well as tax deductible. 

Max .... 10+ years old, has been a resident since 2012. Max reacts aggressively toward strangers and although he has mellowed out in his senior years with some visitors to the rescue, he is unpredictable about what sets him off with others. Max has been and is being sponsored by GPRCI supporters Chris and Dana. Chris is a long time volunteer who Max knows and trusts. He enjoys very much when Chris visits. Thank you Chris and Dana.

Nakoma.....8 year old female Pyrenees mix has pretty severe stranger fear aggression. With repeated visits Nakoma gets comfortable with new people who are confident with her and brave enough to ignore her during intros, as our volunteers have proven, but she barks and snarls aggressively at new people when approached on her home turf quite sure they are up to no good. Nakoma is one who gets a good bit of inside time as she is a perfectly behaved couch potato most of the time but requires her kennel space when anyone she doesn't know is on or coming on property.  


Sadie.....3 year old Pyrenees Komondor mix. Sadie was not socialized well when younger.  Her lack of socialization has resulted in Sadie being untrusting and somewhat unpredictable with strangers, especially on home turf and with her strong guardian genetics. We changed Sadie's status from adoptable to sanctuary after she started exhibiting escalating territorial aggressive behavior toward strangers/visitors.  

Bentley...6 year old male with confinement and separation issues with us since mid 2017. Bentley requires our heaviest fortress of a kennel when he cannot be outside or supervised closely inside. Not much holds this guy in or keeps him out of things if he puts his mind to it. He is smart and very single minded. It took a long time when he arrived but he has adjusted well now, feels at home and secure, and no longer needs the heavy anti-anxiety meds he arrived with.

animal.description:
My name is BAKO and I'm a handsome 10 yr young  M Blue Amstaff/Pitbull Terrier. I'm 66 lbs of PURE GREEK GOD! I was surrendered by my owner due to MOVING OVERSEAS. I was sad to see my owner move and leave me behind,  but he was worried because I'm a senior that the flight would be too stressful for me as I've never been crated/contained.. but it's ok.. I'm glad to have stayed here as I'm ready to move forward to a new life adventure with new hoomans! I'm a very sweet, easy going, fun loving, happy go lucky guy. I like everyone I meet but I haven't met alot of dogs ,  so I'm a little socially ackward with other dogs. When I see them on my walks I get very excited to greet them and can be a little pushy but I've never gotten snarky or snappy.. so I could use some help in the dog socialization dept. I just need to hang out with more dogs so I can get used to them. I used to live with a cat so I'm fine with cats. I'm fine with young kids in passing but have never lived with any kids so I think older kids ages 7 yrs+ would be best. I'm in great shape/health for a senior and people can't believe my age because I'm lively, have medium energy and love to go for walks.  My back legs can be a little cranky so it's best if I don't have to walk up too many stairs and a home in the suburbs with a yard would be ideal/best... but an apt with an elevator would be fine too. I'm SUCH AN EASY GOING SPECIAL guy and a TOTAL LOVE BUG!!  I like to snuggle next to you on the couch or bed and I'm always up for a game of fetch inside or out! I'm JUST THE BEST!!! and an AMBASSADOR for MY BREED.  I'm looking for that wonderful person/couple/family who will LOVE & APPRECIATE me for the rest of my golden years!! If that's you.. pls come meet me today!

For more info/application - PLS EMAIL: INFO@TAILSOFLOVERESCUE.ORG

animal.description: Hi!  Do you live within 4 hours of Kansas City and are you looking for a handsome pup like me? My name is Lloyd and I'm almost 3 years old. As you can see from my photos, I'm a really happy guy. I have lots of energy and like to run around my fenced yard. But I also enjoy relaxing with my foster family. I love to cuddle and to give kisses! I also like to go on short walks once I'm familiar with the neighborhood and with my people. I'm pretty shy when I meet someone new. You see, I grew up in a puppy mill and then lived on a farm for a while where I didn't get much socialization. I also have an eye issue that I was born with that makes it hard for me to see well in really bright light, but I don't let that slow me down. I have a pretty great foster home and I love playing with the other dogs here. Sometimes I even get to go to doggy day care, where I'm a good boy. I have not met any cats yet so I don't know what I'd be like with them. What I want more than anything is to have my very own forever home. I've been waiting so patiently!  Are you the right one?  I'd love to have a house with a fenced yard to play in - and maybe another nice dog or two. Older kids would be fine, if they're gentle and nice, but really little ones might be too scary for me. I'm currently being fostered in the Kansas City area. If you live in the midwest and are interested in a happy, snuggly, shy boy like me, visit www.savingshibas.com/adopt to start the process of becoming approved to adopt from SIRA.

Annie s a 2.5 year old, 40 lb Australian Kelpie mix. Annie is a beautiful girl, but she is a bit shy, especially when meeting new people.  Annie needs an adopter who will be very patient with her, and understand that it may take awhile for her to warm up and settle into her new home. Annie had anxiety issues when she first came into foster care at Humane Tomorrow.  Her anxiety is being successfully treated with medication, so adopters need to be willing to continue her medication for the forseeable future. The cost of the meds is about $20 per month. Annie is worth the little bit of extra effort!  
Annie is very smart, and needs physical and mental stimulation. Once Annie settles in, she is a very happy dog.  She smiles and wiggles with delight when she is with her people.  Nothing is more important to her than pleasing her people, so she will be easy to train with positive reinforcement methods.  Annie prefers people companions to other dog companions, so she needs to be an only dog. 
Annie is crate trained, housebroken, and so deserving of a forever home! Please submit your application to adopt Annie at www.humanetomorrow.org.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.If interested in any of our animals for adoption, or to foster an animal, please fill out the respective application here to get the process started. Visit our FAQ webpage for commonly asked questions about our adoption/foster process.
Picasso is a very sweet, loving boy that loves to cuddle With his people. He also likes to spend time outside. He does not like other dogs so he is very reactive on the leash. He needs a home with no other pets and no kids. Picasso is a shy boy when it comes to new visitors so he will need a quiet home with very little traffic. He is crate trained, up to date on shots, neutered and house trained. Picasso will not be a good fit for an apartment, townhouse or condo. If you are interested in meeting or adopting Picasso please fill out an online application. Questions to cbrookszy@yahoo.com.Last Day Dog Rescue now microchips all animals before adoption. Microchips are implanted between the animals shoulder blades and are a permanent form of identification. The microchips are registered to Last Day Dog Rescue with the adopter's info added once adopted. If the animal is ever lost and slips his/her collar/tags the microchip allows the finder to know who to contact if scanned for a microchip. Animals MUST still have a collar with tags on at all times. Per our contract, we take all our animals back if for any reason you can't keep your adopted animal.

Please understand the statements about this animal are based upon the foster home's evaluation of the animal. The animal might behave differently (negatively or positively) in your home. While the animal might be good with the current foster's dogs, cats, children, etc., it may not be with your animal(s) or children. The animal may be housebroken or litter trained in the home of the foster but may relapse in your home. The animal is represented to the public as it performs in the foster home and any statements made regarding the animal are conditional to that foster home setting. Please understand that statements made regarding this animal are simply overviews and are not guaranteed.

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our animals. Visual breed identification in animals is unreliable so for most of the animals we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each animal as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our animals based on personality, not by breed label.

Thank you for looking through our list of animals needing forever homes and choosing rescue first. We appreciate you stopping by.

animal.description: CHERUB is a 4 year old Terrier reported as a stray on 1/13/20, possibly dumped, running up and down the road, seemingly confused. When this guy came in, he had a growth on his left bottom eyelid, which was removed during his neuter surgery. Normally, each resident is photographed for media once, but between having his eye cared for and having a less than stellar first round of pictures, thought it'd be good to retake and what a difference it made! Cherub's first impression wasn't the best and one can tell by his photos - the one where his tail is tucked is on 1/17 and the other standing is from 2/7. At his 1/17 session, he pulled something awful on the lead, then in the open clammed up with insecurity, would not sit, was unresponsive to treats and toys and seemed oblivious to the handler and photographer. Flash forward to 2/7 and Cherub was more relaxed, walked heaps better, was more congenial and even sat for treats, albeit he could use some work on patience. Can't help but think that having his eye growth removed and having some time to decompress made a world of difference. Cherub's adoption fee is $150 and helps cover his neuter, worming, vaccinations, microchip, monthly heart worm, flea and tick preventive and care while at CCHS.

animal.description:
This sweet girl is Gladys. Gladys was found hanging out with one of our other rescue dogs when he got loose from his foster family. We soon found out that she has been a stray for several months in a neighborhood and had a litter of pups under someone's storage building. The pups had went to homes but no one could catch mom. With the help of a professional dog recovery team we were able to trap Gladys and have been teaching her about being a house dog. She is a very sweet girl and has never once shown an ounce of aggression. She has no self confidence at all and cowers when you talk to her, pet her, or try to take pictures. However, when she is outside in a secure fence playing with the other dogs her head is held high, she is wagging her tail, and she is playing playing playing. She loves other dogs and has to be in a home with another dog. She is not great on a leash but we are working on that. She is house trained and crate trained. We do require that she go to a home with a privacy fenced yard that is very secure or someone who will let us help them secure their fence. And her new home has to have another confident happy dog to play with her. She is estimated to be about 2 years old and 35 lbs. We have had her spayed, vaccinated and microchipped. 
Email crystal@hartmanshaven.org
Please do not inquire unless you have a secure privacy fence and at least 1 other dog. She cannot be adopted to anyone in an apartment complex.

Meet Joey! This handsome boy is what we think is a Chow/Golden Retriever mix. He is soooo soft. Joey will need a very special home with a family that has lots of patience. It took us 7 months to finally capture him and has taken a few months to get him domesticated again. Joey LOVES other dogs and would do best with at least 1 other dog in the home. He is currently in a foster home with a 6 foot fence privacy fence and electric wire that stops him from digging out and we have had no issues. animal.description:
OK Folks it's Today's Terrible Trivia Time (4T) ... again ... 

So, here's your opportunity in today's first round of Today's Terrible Trivia Time (4T) to win absolutely nothing ... can you just hardly wait?  Me either, so let's get started!

OK, here's today's question:    What do we call someone who puts their dog on a 3 year regimen of PROZAC, a pharmaceutical the use of which is known to cause .... AGGRESSION ... as a treatment for "separation anxiety"??    

what?  Can you repeat your answer?  "Idiot"?    Well yes, obviously "idiot" is a good 5 letter word.  Moron also works.  We could go on but .... 

So, I am Malakai, a Neapolitan Mastiff, born a little more than 5 years ago (11/2014) .. and I lost my home while on PROZAC for separation anxiety.  Sadly, yes, I bit my mommy's hubby.  Twice.  Mommy worked for a vet but was unaware that behavior modification could have been a real alternative to giving me a THREE YEAR RUN ON PROZAC.

So now my little system is finally PROZAC-free.  There has been no more aggression (of course, I haven't seen mommy or hubby since that second chomp) ... but I digress.  Yep, prozac-free and I'm a very affectionate, happy guy who is social with other dogs.   I also haven't destroyed the house.  BORING.  But Lisa says that's a good thing.

Obviously, my new mommy Lisa says I can't go to any home with kids.  Yeh, I get it those little guys would stress out Mother Theresa.

I would love an owner who is home most of the time. I am very affectionate. I get along with other dogs.  I want to go home with an experienced Neo owner.

No experience with Neos?  Talk with Lisa.  Maybe we can train you.
animal.name: Malikai

Completely unsocialized. 

 Will NOT bite people despite being very fearful.  

Lived in a crate all their life except to go potty outside.  

NO CHILDREN.  

Needs a Sheltie savvy, patient, and loving adopter WHO WILL TAKE EVERY PRECAUTION TO PREVENT THEM FROM BOLTING OUT OF THE HOUSE OR CAR for the entirety of their lives.  

Off leash is a risk you should never take.

This Sheltie kid is fearful of the world and people and will bolt at the slightest opportunity. 

NEVER risk his life by taking him off leash outside of your enclosed home or enclosed yard. 

A gate of some sort is needed at the front door to prevent bolting out the front door. 

A car restraint/seatbelt and appropriate harness is needed to keep them safe and prevent them from bolting out of your vehicle. This is not optional.

This Sheltie kid is fearful but will not bite. They are soft and sweet but afraid. 

This Sheltie kid needs a dog savvy patient and understanding home willing to work with them and their needs.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Do you love to cuddle? I am your gal!Did you see my adorable face?
I am a fun loving girl, who loves to crawl up on my mom's lap and cuddle. I play hard all day with my foster siblings.
Did someone say water? How about mud? I figured out if I get dirty, mom gives me a bath! I love water and especially love it when mom scrubs me with great smelling bubbles and then rubs me dry with a big fluffy towel. I have had as many as 3 bathes in one day! I love water! Sometimes I sit in our empty puppy pool just begging mom to fill it up!
I am an active dog and not suitable for an apartment, nor small children. I will need another dog in the house to keep me happy.
My litter mates and I were orphaned at two weeks old after our mother died. I love to play with my siblings and foster moms dogs! I would love to have an older sibling in my new home to play with and teach me how to be a well mannered pup! I should be around 30-45 pounds when full grown.
Since I am a puppy, I will need a lot of patience and guidance, but if you choose to adopt me I promise to give you tons of love and be the best furever family member! I am working hard on potty training and my adoption fee includes four rounds of shots, rabies shots, neuter and microchip (at a regular vet all of these services would cost over $500!)

=========================================================

Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
Are you one of those rare people who can leave a Christmas present sit under the tree for weeks without shaking it or peeking inside? Do you respect those "Do Not Open Until December 25th" gift tags? If so, you might just be the kind of person Maggie needs! This girl needs a patient human who is okay "waiting for the present" - which in her case, the present is endless snuggles and kisses.

Maggie takes time to warm up to new people, but once she does, she is the sweetest pup. She needs a dedicated human who will use positive reinforcement training to continue teaching her "how to dog." She is a 60lb, 2 1/2 year old pit mix who is muzzle trained and knows sit, down, touch, drop it, and go to your mat. She loves routine and will even put herself to bed at night. 

Maggies Forever Family Wish List:
 Family willing to continue training
 Adult only home 
 Privacy fence (no invisible fence, no chanin link fence, at least 6ft tall)
 Family who is home frequently with few visitors
 Confident, laid back resident dog (or no other dogs if family is home more often than not)
 Single family home (no apartments)
 Dog handling experience 

If this describes you & you're ready for a new best friend, apply for Maggie at RESCUEDohio.org. Maggie's adoption fee is $300.

animal.description: Mallory is ready to prove that she's the strongest girl you know! A bit of a lone wolf but not afraid to show you some love, this big girl will make a great companion for an active home ready to help her lead a happy life! Mallory is certainly an energetic dog. Great for walks, jogs, or even runs if the weather is right, she wants nothing more than to play the day away! Mallory can be leash reactive so playtime with other dogs won't always be right for her, but that just means she's got more energy for time with you. Even at home, Mallory can find ways to play the days away, choosing to get in contests of strength with new visitors and her rope toy. But she also knows to read the room and lower that energy down a bit when needed. And you never need to question just how much she loves you when she tries to cuddle! Even though Mallory is a big girl she wants to make sure her WHOLE body is touching you to show how much she cares. Be careful if you let her on your bed - she can be a bit of a bed hog and spread across before you know it! Mallory would like to be the only pup in your life, as she can be a bit of a loner when she wants. But this sweet girl has plenty of love to go around and gets along swimmingly with strangers that are willing to show her a little playful attention! And she's sure to be the best companion possible for you. Are you ready to enrich her life and grow a powerful new lifetime bond? Come see Mallory today!

animal.description:
Eva is a sweet shepherd/heeler mix and is approximately 2 years old.  Her mom was Priscilla who we had in our care with her last litter.  Eva is from Priscilla’s last litter born on the reservation before we rescued Priscilla.  When Eva was almost a year she became pregnant and was brought into our care.  She was very scared coming into foster care and (just like her mom) escaped her foster home within the first few days.  She was on the run for 7 days and finally we were able to bring her back into our care.  She has learned to love her foster mom and hasn’t tried to escape since.  She just needed time to realize how safe and loved she was.  She is still unsure of new people and has really been more protective of her home.  It will take her time to adjust to a new home and humans. She’d probably do best in a home that doesn’t have a lot of visitors.  When new people make her nervous and move, she might nip at them.  She’ll need a VERY patient home that is willing to work on gaining her trust. She does best when you get low and let her smell you and have treats. 

She loves to play with the other fosters.  She does play a lot with her mouth and mouths the others and her foster mom when she plays. She is a BIG puppy that doesn’t always realize her size and strength when playing.  Car rides have been scary for her and she would benefit from more fun car rides where she goes somewhere fun.  She is NOT a fan of crates in a car, but will go in a wire crate at home if she has to (she prefers not to be in crates and will try to get out). 

She began showing similar signs as her mother did with having a cancerous tumor.  She was diagnosed with a venereal tumor (same as her mom Priscilla) the end of March 2020.  She had surgery to remove the tumor and went through 4 rounds of chemo and all looks good.  She recovered well and the vet visits did help her with getting into the car but she still usually throws up on car rides. 

She would really benefit from patient, consistent training and is very treat motivated. She will need a tall, secure fence as well. She seems to love to sleep under her foster’s mom bed, on the couch or on a dog bed.  A harness would be best when working on leash training.  She is potty trained by way of a doggy door.  She is a happy girl and would LOVE to have a buddy to play with.  She’d do best in a home without small kids since she does play a little rough and doesn’t know her own size.  She also chases and stresses out the cats in her foster home so we'd recommend a home without cats.

With time, patience and love she'll become a great companion for her human.

Her adoption fee is $100.00.  She is spayed and is up to date on vaccinations including rabies.  She will require a tall secure above ground fenced yard.  We require that our dogs be allowed in their family home and be allowed to sleep inside at night.  An adoption contract is completed and signed at the time of adoption.  

To inquire about adopting this dog or to find out more about her, please contact her foster Mom Stacee at ringo406@hotmail.com.

animal.description:
Kammie is a shy 8 year old lab mix. 

(Kammie is not yet ready for adoption, she needs to gain her confidence in foster care) 

Kammie was found homeless with her 3 babies. All of Kammie's other pups did not survive the conditions they were in prior to arriving at the shelter. Poor Kammie has lost so much already, it's time she gains something. A home and loving family can help start making up for that. Because she has had so much trauma, this girl is timid, but has not shown any aggression when she is approached. She even gets along well with other dogs! Kammie is an older dog, so we want her last years to be filled with happiness. She should not leave this world having only known loss.

From her foster: She is so gentle and sweet. It definitely takes her a bit to get comfortable, but it makes the tail wags even more special when you get them! Kammie took a few days to get potty trained, but they all do as you know. She hasn't had an accident inside since the third day we had her. She has been great with the puppy and my dog, but she doesn't seem to like my cats. She growls and barks when she sees them and they're shy so they stay in our bedroom most of the time. We gave her a bath a few days after they settled in and she did really well! She's slow to walk on a leash, but she has improved so much in just one week. She takes treats very gently and doesn't make a peep when I put her in her kennel at night and when we're leaving for work. 

She is such a gentle girl who just needs some TLC to know what love is- she deserves it!! She's not super active, but I've seen glimpses of her get excited with my dog and want to play a little. It breaks my heart to think of all the years of hard living she's endured and I know she will be a great addition to a family willing to show her how great life as a dog can be! 


https://youtu.be/onmQPEXxHAQ

If you are interested in these pups, please submit an application through our website aaanimalrescue.org. Please feel free to email with any questions allaboardanimalrescue@gmail.com.


Breed and size disclosure: As a rescue all of our dogs come to us from high-kill shelters or other rescues, so we do not get a lot of background or information on these dogs. We occasionally receive the mother with the puppies, but in most cases both parents are unknown. Because of this we do not know the full breeding of the dogs. We are required to list the dogs based on the breeds provided to us on their records, but they are all mixed breeds as far as we know, and we cannot guarantee the actual breeds of any of these dogs. Since the full breeding of the dogs is unknown we can also only give you an educated guess on the full-grown size of the dogs. All of the current information we have on the dogs is listed in their bio above. More information may be available at our adoption event, since a lot of the fosters turn in report cards on how the dog has done in their care when they drop them off. 

Adoption Process: If you are interested in adopting from us, the first step of our adoption process is to fill out an application online at http://aaanimalrescue.org/adoption_app.html. It takes us 24-48 hours to process your application and get back to you, via email. Applications turned in Friday afternoon or Saturday morning will not be processed since we are preparing for or at our adoption event. We do have applications on site at our events, but are not always able to approve them at that time and many of the dogs will already have holds on them, so we suggest you fill out an application prior to attending an adoption event. We can place a hold on one dog per approved applicant after a deposit fee has been received, please do not ask to hold a dog if you have not turned in an application and been approved, for the first hour of our adoption event, so that they can get the first chance to meet and hopefully adopt that dog. After the first hour of the event all dogs are available on a first come, first serve basis. If you already have an approved application on file, there will just be more paperwork and the adoption fee at the event, but you will be able to take home the dog/puppy that day. Since we are foster based and do not have a location, our dogs are only available to meet at our events, unless otherwise noted.

animal.description:
After 2 years of searching, Weeble is ready to find his forever home. 

Here is a little note Weeble wrote his potential new family: 

Hi, my name is Weeble and I’m a little bit different! I have cerebellar hypoplasia (CH) that causes me to be wobbley, but that doesn’t stop me from being a big goofball! My condition doesn’t require medication and I am a very healthy boy! I have been looking for my forever home since I was a puppy, and really need someone to just give me a chance! I love my foster family, and I know they wish they could keep me forever but unfortunately they can’t. I am potty trained and love my crate! I love going for walks, but I need to stay close to my owners to keep them safe! The world can be pretty scary, so I do my best to protect my home from strangers. I really don’t care too much for strangers, and would prefer a nice quiet room when you have company. 

Because dogs in a previous home weren’t so kind to me, I really would prefer to be the only animal in your life.  But don’t worry, I have so much love to give you won’t need anyone else! 

I am truly one of a kind, and I know we could be the best of friends. Please give me a chance to show you. 


Weebles adoption fee has been sponsored by one of our supporters. He is neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, current on flea and heartworm prevention, and very healthy! 

To adopt or learn more about me, apply today at farfetcheddogrescue.org

animal.description:
If you are seeing this dog, she is AVAILABLE. We hide them from view once adopted. 

Meet Cookie! She is a gorgeous beagle that's estimated DOB is 4/10/17. Cookie is currently in one of our amazing foster homes and her foster mom can't say enough wonderful things about her. Cookie is an absolute joy that lights up a room with her sweet and loving disposition. This girl loves people and loves to be close to you. Her favorite thing in the world is a belly rub and she will never hesitate to roll over on her back and invite you to rub her belly. This sweet girl also loves to snuggle up on the couch with you. She loves to go for walks and loves to play ball. Cookie is dog and cat friendly. Oh and did we mention that she's house broken and leash trained? This girl is the whole package deal! She's just waiting for someone to choose her and give her the forever home she's always deserved. 

Cookie has seizures that are controlled with medication. She takes her meds like a champ!

This dog is heartworm positive. We have started them on the "slow-kill" method of heartworm treatment, but we advise adopters to work with their vets to determine a plan of action. Their adopter will continue treatment once adopted, and arrange a treatment plan with their vet. Dogs with heartworms lead long, happy lives post-treatment! Cookie has seizures that are controlled with medication. 

There is no set adoption fee for this dog. In lieu of an adoption fee we are asking for a donation to our shelter to help us care for these babies and keep them safe. We do not receive any funding so any donation is greatly appreciated.

We can offer transport for in-state adopters that cannot make the trip to the shelter.There is a flat transport fee of $50 to have this dog brought to you. (This does not apply to meet-and-greets, which must be done at the shelter by appointment only). 

ADOPTION FEE AND HEALTH INFORMATION 
Upon adoption, she will have received: age appropriate vaccines (2 DHPP vaccine), (Bordetella vaccine), (Rabies vaccine if 12 weeks and older), up to date on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, spay or neuter of pet, bi-weekly worming, microchip, fostering costs, and health certificate. 

You must fill out an application to adopt! The application is below. Please copy and paste it into your browser. 

https://goo.gl/forms/YKPbHaym6keQA6772 

APPLY 
Isn't she sweet? Wondering what's next? You MUST fill out an application to adopt. Please copy and paste the Google form URL below: 

https://goo.gl/forms/YKPbHaym6keQA6772 

Once you have submitted an application, we do our best to work efficiently to process them. 

FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS 
Q: Where is she located? 
A: She is currently at our shelter in Arkansas. She can only be adopted locally due to her positive heart worm status. 

Q: It feels scary adopting without meeting the pup first. What if he isn't the right fit for our home? 
A: We know it can feel scary and that's why we offer a FULL refund of your adoption fee within the first two weeks if for some reason it's not the right fit. We want our adopters to feel confident and we want the best situation for our pups. If in that 2 weeks you feel it is not working out, we can rehome the dog and refund your adoption fee. All we ask is that you foster the dog until we find them a new home! 

Q: I have more questions!! Who do I contact? 
A: Please e-mail adopt@humanesocietyofthedelta.org directly. We DO NOT answer adoption questions or inquiries on any other platform. 

Q: I am under 21, will you adopt to me? 
A: Unfortunately, we do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21. 

Q: I would like to surprise my family with a dog! Can I do this? 
A: Unfortunately, no. If there is more than one decision-maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement. 

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

animal.description:
Meet Bread and Butter,
These two beauties are 7-8 month old female hound mixes. They are a special case that is looking for the right forever home with a big heart. They are available for Foster to adopt.

These little guys suffer from Megasophagus or MegaE for short. MegaE is a generalized enlargement of the esophagus. 
-a muscular tube connecting the throat to the stomach 

How do you treat this, some medication and the Bailey chair. These little pups are practicing eating in this chair. Once they’re done eating, they sit in the chair for 30 mins to allow the food to digest. This is new to them and they need a little training, but we’re working on it!

Bread is full of energy, Butter is shy. They both want a family to love them! If you have any questions or would like more information, please fill out an application and you will be contacted by a TriCounty Dog Rescue Volunteer.

They are available Individually.  :)

animal.description:
All of our dogs are housed in private homes, we do not have a store or a shelter. We do not show dogs to interested parties until they have an approved adoption application. If you are interested in adopting one of our dogs, please fill out an adoption application on our website www.helpingshepherdsofeverycolor.com You may also find us on facebook: Helping Shepherds of Every Color Rescue.

2/9/2020 Taz (was Zing) is being returned to the rescue due to some personal issues with his family.

Taz is very Energetic and loves to run. He loves to go to the dog park and play with other dogs but for his home life it's best if he's an only dog. He's a little food aggressive with other animals not with people at all. He's not ok with little kids. He might be good with older kids, like around 8 and up though. He is also cautious when meeting new people but once he knows them he's great. He loves sleeping on the sofa and getting belly rubs. He's not big on toys but every once in awhile he'll find one that he loves. He is also very nervous about getting his nails trimmed. Less is definitely more with him. I would not try to Restrain him, if you do then he'll need a muzzle on. He does also have a little bit of anxiety and hates to be tied up. He does love his crate though, it's like "his" place if that makes sense.

6/29/2020: Taz is NOT good with cats or other small animals. He is settling in to his new foster home. He gets along with some dogs better than others. He needs time to warm up to new people but he is very loving when he is comfortable.

animal.description:
Bowie is a goofy, beautiful boy with the most interesting grayish, brownish coat. He looks one color inside and another color out in the sun! 

Bowie was picked up as a stray by the local police department in our town and since we have no animal control officers or city shelters in our neck of the woods, he sat for weeks in a cage in a shed. He was very timid and many of the officers were afraid of him because he would growl when they approached. They called us to do a behavior assessment and upon walking in with a can of vienna sausage, we found that Bowie did not have a mean bone in his body, he was merely scared. We recommended a home with no cats and no small children and unfortunately the officers allowed a private citizen to take him in for a short time before re-homing him via a free to good home ad in the classifieds. The home that responded to the free ad had him less than 24 hours because he chewed through their bathroom door, and sadly, attacked and killed one of their cats. At that time, we intervened and Critters Inc. became Bowie's 4th home. 

In the many months he has been with us, Bowie has enjoyed the company of 6 other dogs and he ADORES each and every one of them. He also co-exists with the more than 50 cats here awaiting adoption. Bowie was evaluated by a professional trainer and tested with dogs from 20 lbs and up and also with cats. This evaluation revealed that Bowie has an interrupt-able prey drive and on the occasion that he does focus on a cat, he can be redirected with a quick verbal correction. Bowie has been through A LOT in his life and we believe he is only 2-3 years old.

 Bowie's adopters will be thoroughly screened including a home visit, and a fenced yard is required. Bowie will do best in a home with other dogs to play with but he will not be placed into a home with cats, other small animals, or dogs under 30 lbs for any reason. We need to find a home where his needs are met and where we can be assured it will be his forever home. This guy has lots of kisses, snuggles, and play time to give and we hope everyone looks beyond the poor circumstances he was placed into in the past and helps him to find a bright future with a home of his very own.

All dogs have been dewormed, spayed/neutered, microchipped, Heartworm tested, and have age appropriate vaccinations including DA2PP and Rabies.

animal.description:
Skye is a beautiful girl who came to us from a rural shelter. She was very shy, unhealthy, listless, and didn't much want to be around anyone at first. Since she has been with our rescue, Skye has been looking for that pot of gold at the end of her rainbow. She has learned to trust people again and she has been socialized by her foster mom to new situations, sights, and sounds. Skye has blossomed into a loving and playful girl that enjoys life. She lives for walks and fresh air and she is super gentle on a leash. Her new found joie de vivre has stolen the hearts of our fosters and staff; she will steal yours too. 

Skye is 5 years old and weighs 75 pounds. She is spayed, fully vaccinated, and being treated for heart worms.  She plays nicely with dogs that understand she's in charge. 

Here at NMAR, we don't just find good homes for our dogs, we find the the specific good home for each specific dog. While we work towards those matches, our dogs are safe and happy in foster homes, or in our home-like shelter, where they have the chance to learn some life skills and show us what they need to be happy and healthy.

REQUIREMENTS: Skye needs a home where she's the only pet. Skye is not cat friendly. 

Adoption fee is $195 and includes: spay/neuter, parvo/distemper series of shots, rabies (if dog is old enough), bordatella, heartworm treatment while here, worming, and microchip.

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting Sky, please visit our website and fill out an adoption application: NorthMeckAnimalRescue.org

animal.description:
Get ready for your daily dose of caffeine AND serotonin. Gabby's gleeful energy and total zest for life is infectious! Gabby happens to be deaf but that certainly doesn't slow her down. This spirit, feisty girl is queen of the zoomies and is all about getting up and about to explore and play. Gabby would benefit from an active but patient home that can help her learn a routine, exercise her mind and body, and continue to learn signs. She seems to be incredibly smart, and is a ready sponge for learning! Once she gets her yayas out, Gabby shows her sweet and affectionate side. And she has that spark of mischief to always keep you laughing. With her intelligence and athleticism, we think Gabby might thrive with sports or agility training. In the summer, she loves nothing more than dancing and spinning in the sprinkler! Gabby is around 1 or 2 years old. Gabby is currently living in a foster home. To set up a meet with her or find out more information, please contact her foster at david.ager@gmail.com!? 63 lbs.
Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
 Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

 Hours:
 10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
 10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

  The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.  
 Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. Some dogs with special needs may require a rescue to pull. You can either stop in during our open hours to meet a dog, or set up a meet and greet with your dog, which allows us to get the dog out of his/her cage for some exercise before you arrive. To set up a meet and greet or to inquire about a dog’s special needs, please email us at citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us.

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.
Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DHPP, Rabies, Bordetella and Canine Influenza vaccines, thought you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.

He gets excited over his meals, his walks and any wildlife he comes across (he caught a bird the other day; RIP)...he does not like cats...so, just a normal dachshund with no quirky traits!Mr. Gump is fully vetted and, like many older ladies or gentlemen, has certain meds he needs to enhance his senior step! After an initial burst of energy, he is great on leash on quiet trails and parks, away from traffic. He likes to walk along, watching and sniffing everything.

We've seen Buster around a few other dogs. When another dog scares him, he tends to move away to avoid them. He's curious and interested in friendly dogs. We think Buster might do well with a laid-back, friendly, tolerant dog.

Buster has had some scary experiences, but he thrives with reward-based training. He did great in training at South Austin Dog Center, and his trainers will continue to work with a foster or adopter.

I can be very silly, reacting cutely to animal noises on the tv or Alexa devices. I also sometimes bark a quick “thank you” when I’m given my food at mealtimes.

Overall, though, I would love to just follow you around all day and snuggle when the day is over.

animal.description:
Harriet is a true diamond in the rough. This street dog has likely lived her entire life without a home and learned to survive with the resources she had. It was sure luck that she had a litter of puppies and an amazing rescue was able to save them and trap Harriet to get her to safety. Harriet and puppies were then transferred to our shelter where she managed to escape while trying to unload her. Again, she lived off the streets for 4 weeks, eating whatever food she could. It was a miracle that we were able to catch her again and was discovered she was caught in a hog snare that was digging deep into her skin. Harriet is now healed up from that and at a healthy weight but she has unfortunately also tested positive for heart worms. She has begun her 2 month treatment but this poor girl can't seem to catch a break. 

Harriet is very shy right now and not trusting of staff. She has never tried to bite but avoids us as much as she can. She has a long road ahead of her, mentally and physically, but she is on the mends. 

If you would like to make a donation towards Harriet's ongoing care, please click the link below: 
http://www.hillcountryspca.com/healing-hearts.html

animal.description:
Pip and Athena are two of the cutest puppies you will ever meet!

Pip is the shorter one with floppy ears and Athena is taller with straight ears.

They are 9-10months old & approximately 15-20 pounds. They came from a family who could no longer keep them. Another rescue took their siblings and we welcomed these two sweet girls into the rescue.

They’ve been through a lot in their short life. They were picked up as strays so we don't know how they & their siblings survived but apparently life was not good in the beginning.  They came to us scared and are now the life of the party.  Once they know you and feel comfortable, they will keep you smiling and laughing with their antics!

Their negative is: We recently found out they don't like all men.  Their current foster is a man but he has other dogs so they're ok with him.  They were adopted for less than a week to a nice family and they did not like the son or the husband once they got into the home. They were great upon meeting them but 4 days in and they started becoming protective over the mom.  The trainer we sent them to was a man & he feels they would do better in an all female house or with a man who is nurturing. .

Pip is the life of the party and will worm her way into your heart within minutes of meeting you.

Athena is shy and it takes a couple minutes for her to warm up. She has a tendency to follow her sister.

*** PIP AND ATHENA MUST BE ADOPTED TOGETHER

These girls get along with all size dogs.  If you are looking for a pair of beauties who will warm your heart and make you smile, please fill out an application.

https://www.muttsinneed.org/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
Look who is FINALLY ready for adoption!! Jordan! He has been in our rescue over a year. You all raised nearly $6,000 for Jordan to get much needed cataract surgery. He is now 8 months post-op and has been given the all-clear! 
Jordan is about 5 years old and 20 lbs. He was adopted at about 18 months and returned to NHAR two years later in rough shape. He had been diagnosed with diabetes nearly a year earlier and was not being treated for it. As a result, he had the premature cataracts we ultimately removed with the wonderful Dr. McIllnay at Veterinary Eye Specialists in Omaha. 
It has taken every ounce of this year to get him healthy. He could not have his surgery for six months because his blood sugars were so out of whack. The post-op surgery requirements were many. He was taking up to six eye drops five times a day. He has been through hell and back, and now he can finally start looking for his forever home.
Jordan is a ball of fire. He is all terrier. He is super smart. He is very active. He loves to ride in the car and go for walks. He thinks he is the star of the show and loves to show off and get attention. He is also a bit of a bully with dogs, so he pairs well with an alpha. He kennels well. He is also very stubborn. He can get nippy if you grab him or try to correct him sternly. With positive reinforcement and love, he does great. For this reason, we will not be adopting him to a home with small children. He needs to have everyone around him know how to handle him.
Jordan is going to need someone to make a lifetime commitment to his medical care. He will continue to have follow up appointments in Omaha for his eyes that must be attended; his adoption contract will require it. We can’t take $6,000 in donations and not have his new owner follow through. He will have two different eye drops that he will need every day, potentially for the rest of his life. 
He is also still diabetic. That requires specific food, two insulin shots a day, and vet visits at least twice a year to do blood work. And of course, all of the basics. He needs his regular shots, heart worm preventative, flea and tick treatment, and the occasional dental. All in all, you can expect to pay roughly $200 a month for his care for his maintenance, on top of the semi-annual vet visits.
Jordan has all the regular care the rest of our fosters have too. He’s neutered, up to date on shots, microchipped, on heart worm preventative, and has had his teeth cleaned in January, 2020.
We want to be sure to find Jordan the perfect home. If you think you could fit the bill, please click on the link below to fill out an adoption application. His adoption fee is $135. 

https://form.jotform.com/50308432400137

All dogs listed here, require an application for adoption, before any questions or meet and greet appointment. 
Find the application at www.cowdogrescue.com
Please - we will not answer questions/inquiries prior to an application -

.4-24-17 Trident, and Tethys, come into rescue as another litter, from Momma Mia, we believe. They are around 8 months old, and are a work in progress with collar, leash, and socialization. ACD experience is required for these, because they need extra guidance. Our adoption fee ($250) covers the age appropriate spay / neutering, heart worm testing, rabies, distemper combo, microchipping and any other necessary medical that a dog may need. Please consider a rescue that comes to you with all of the routine medical (and then some) already done.

Need to find the application? Please visit our new website at www.cowdogrescue.com Contact Monica at (989) 330-5147, Director of AuCaDo Rescue, for questions about adoption process. If you are looking for a certain rescue, let me know, as we always have rescues waiting to come here.

Dontate-A-Thundershirt ProgramClick HereDonate-A-Thundershirt Program

PLEASE NOTE: AuCaDo Rescue is not a public shelter. This dog is being fostered in a private home / kennel until adoption. Jax is a special needs dog in that he must have had some rough handling in the past. He is very particular about how his collar is handled and likes you to handle it slowly.  Brisk movements around his collar from behind him surprise him and make him be defensive. Therefore he needs an experienced adult to help him learn to trust again. We think adult only / no other pet household. 

He is very food motivated so all you need to do is show him a treat and he will do what you are asking. He has nice long legs and a very bushy and full coat so he would be perfect in the more northern climates. He would be great for a couple who want a companion dog make them feel safer. He is not a big barker but very inquisitive and observant. He loves being in the yard and doesn’t try to climb or dig in the yards we have. He is currently in Texas waiting for his forever home. His adoption fee is 180. He is a wonderful dog and with the right family will make a nice companion.
