animal.description:
Barney is a sweet, sensitive doofus with many layers. At his core, he has a huge heart, and is a goofy, playful, and affectionate. He has an endearing curiosity and wonder for the world, and he seems to love taking in nature and the outdoors. Wrapped around this is a big layer of insecurity, which makes him sensitive and unsure in new environments. He can take a while to be fully comfortable in a new environment and with new people. Barney would benefit from a patient home that can give him some structure and further training so he can feel confident and learn to trust. Once he does, he is an absolute delight for company. His noodly wiggle-butt and permanent frowny face only add to the charm! Currently living in a foster home, Barney has shown that he is housebroken and crate-trained. He is around 1 or 2 years old (still a youngster), and weighs around 75 lbs.  Contact david.ager@gmail.com to learn more about Barney and to set up a meet!
  
Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
 Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

 Hours:
 10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
 10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

  The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.  
 Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. Some dogs with special needs may require a rescue to pull. You can either stop in during our open hours to meet a dog, or set up a meet and greet with your dog, which allows us to get the dog out of his/her cage for some exercise before you arrive. To set up a meet and greet or to inquire about a dog’s special needs, please email us at citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us.

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.
Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DHPP, Rabies, Bordetella and Canine Influenza vaccines, thought you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.

animal.description:
SPECIAL NEEDS: Deaf

REQUIREMENTS:
-Deaf dog + large breed experience
-Owners that are not gone long hours or work from home 
-Another laid back dog in the home
-Adult only preferred, kids over 16 okay
-No apartments, home with fenced yard required

Blanca is a DEAF, 4 year old, 60lb Pitbull mix. She is such a lover and LOVES to give kisses and get cuddles in return. She is an incredibly sweet, gentle and well mannered girl looking for a family who can help her safely navigate and live her life to the fullest as she is missing one of her senses. 

She requires a home that has experience working with and training a deaf dog. She is very smart and treat motivated! She is working on her commands but will need help expanding her knowledge using signs and visual signals. 

Blanca can do well with other dogs with proper introductions. She does not appreciate rambunctious or dominant dogs in her space if she does not know them well. Once she knows them, she does great with other dogs, and will need another laid back dog friend her size or larger in the home, no small dogs. She currently lives with 3 other large/medium dogs. (She is not a dog park dog.)

Blanca LOVES to cuddle and is a great couch or bedtime snuggler. Though she likes to lounge, she also enjoys walks and runs with her foster mom. She will need a family that is extra careful to make sure she is secure for adventures and can’t get loose since she cannot hear! She walks well but can get reactive when she sees other dogs. She is working on that in her foster home.

Blanca is crate and house trained. Kids above 16 due to her size and hearing disability though an adult only home is ideal. Having a properly fenced yard, deaf dog experience and another dog in the home are all required.

Blanca is up to date on shots, microchipped and spayed. Her adoption fee is $400.

When Lisa was first rescued several years ago she had a light limp. She was diagnosed with slight hip dysplasia and we were told that her condition was not severe enough for surgery. 

Last week Lisa injured her leg (torn ACL) and needs surgery to repair. It was also determined that her hip dysplasia has progressed to where she now needs surgery on BOTH hips. 

Poor Lisa needs three surgeries AND she needs to find a quiet home for her successful recovery. 

We would like to to keep her as close by to her vet at the Animal Hospital of Fayetville, NC.

Please consider helping our beautiful girl recover to her happy and energetic self.

animal.description:
*******NO YOUNG CHILDREN*******
******VERY ENERGETIC***********
If you are looking for an instant family you’ve come to the right place. Meet Sugar and Toto; a BEYOND adorable pair of bonded terrier mixes. At just over a year old they are both active, silly, a little crazy and totally lovable. They do everything together and are not often apart. Sugar (the white one, naturally) is the big sister and she’s a little more independent and curious about her environment and the people in it. Toto is like that little brother who follows his big sis everywhere and does what she does. 

They love a good cuddle session at night and will happily receive belly rubs and kisses but during the day Toto and Sugar are exceptionally energetic. They love their daily power walks, no casual strolls from them!  If they aren’t walking they are playing together and tearing up the back yard; a fence in yard is required.

They are still a little wary of strangers and anything new so a family that can expose them to many different situations, environs, and people would be great. Based on their size and current temperament, older children would be preferred. If you can handle double the kisses and 8 crazy-legs you’ll want to meet these two.
For more information please email freetobemerescue@gmail.com or call 518-956-1804. Or you can go online to freetobemerescue.org to submit an application.
Please be advised we only process applications within an hour drive of Albany NY.  Adoption fee $550.00

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 11/08/2018
Reason for being in rescue: Lovingly surrendered by owners because he disliked one of the members in the relationship
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Griff has a bite history
Weight: 60 lbs
Height: 27 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $499

Fence needed? Yes without exception.

What kind of home would be best for me? Griff needs a low traffic home and an experienced dog owner. He needs a home that will offer him both daily physical and mental exercise. He is bright and if he is bored he can be trouble. He wants an owner who will love him but will let him come to him. Patience and a calm, even personality is a must. Grif does much better with women and would be best in a home with only women. He needs to be the only dog and will not do well with children.

What is my personality like? Griff thrives on confident, controlled people who do not show fear. If he thinks you are afraid of him, he will take advantage of you. If he knows you respect him but do not fear him he will lay his heart at your feet.

Griff has been trained under a shock collar and it has created a lot of the challenges we are overcoming. He was shocked when he barked. He was shocked when there was any sort of behavior that was deemed "unacceptable." It has shaped his behavior in such a way that we are now working to unshape that fear and re-establish trust.

Griff is a sweet dog once he knows you. Griff is very timid and takes a while to warm up. He can be a little aggressive in the beginning. He loves to sun bathe outside and is a very calm chill dog when he's comfortable. He's very smart also, he sits and waits for his food and doesn't bark or act crazy. He can resource guard at times also. He does have some barrier aggression when another dog is walking by his run. Griff would enjoy being a couch potato and someone's best friend!!

How do I act when I first meet new people? You have to ignore Griff and let him come to you. Don't reach out to him, let him smell you and get comfortable with you. Once he knows you he is a wonderful, loving companion. Our ops manager can do anything with him.

Other tips and tidbits: Griff's birthday is 4/8/2014.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

Date into Rescue: 2/24/2018
Reason for being in rescue: Pulled from a GA shelter. Doc was seized in neglect case and taken to the shelter.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet, SC
Special Needs? Doc is blind. He also battles skin challenges.
Weight: 30 lbs
Height: unknown
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $1 - I am priceless

Fence needed? Yes. Doc loves to wander in a fenced yard and enjoy the feel of sunshine and grass. He is not a dog that you will walk on a leash.

What kind of home would be best for me? Doc is still learning what it means to be someone's pet. He needs an experienced owner that will work with him to teach him basic commands, reward him with lots of positive affirmations, and give him the time and support he needs to blossom into the dog he can be. Doc is blind. He needs a quiet home with experience to understand vision impaired dogs. Doc needs a home where someone can be with him at all times, and watched when he is outside just to make sure he's safe always since he is older and blind.

What is my personality like? Seven dogs were seized in a neglect case and brought to Carolina Poodle Rescue. As there were seven, they were named for the seven dwarfs. This is Doc. None of the dogs had had much medical care before coming to Carolina Poodle Rescue. We think that none of them had ever been inside a house before either. All of the dogs from this situation were listed as miniature labradoodles.

Doc is a sweet older guy who can still play like a puppy. He has a great temperament and personality in spite of being neglected for much of his life. In a home with a person or people to love him and provide him with stability and training, he would finally know what it's like to be part of a family. Imagine how he might blossom then! He already knows how to be clean in his crate which is a big step toward house training.

Doc can be slightly dog selective but he gets a long really well with most dogs. He isn't food aggressive and knows how to politely take a treat when one is offered. We estimate Doc to be around 11 years old but don't tell him that! He doesn't know that he's an older guy. Doc enjoys sniffing and walking outside when the sun is out. He can also be a total couch potato that loves taking long naps on his sofa during the day.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits:

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

Looking for a back scratching home body to love.Date into Rescue: 05/02/2017
Reason for being in rescue: Link Basil was surrendered to CPR by his owners.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Link needs a home where there are no other dogs. He would do best with a quiet life where he stays within a fenced yard for exercise and has no canine visitors.
Weight: 23 lbs
Height: Estimated 14.5 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Link needs a quiet home that is willing to understand him. On the plus side, because his mother was a poodle. Link is a low shedder. He is not a highly active dog and would be fine for someone who is a homebody and likes to putter around the house. He has not shown us that he needs to run and leap and jump a lot. Link was previously adopted from CPR and returned for biting. Link is not good with other dogs and is barrier aggressive when another dog walks past him. He needs to be in a home where he is the only animal.

What is my personality like? Link arrived at the farm along with siblings due to no fault of his own. Link was previously adopted but returned due to biting. Since being back at the farm he can no longer go out with dogs because he does not get along with them. He needs an experienced home willing to learn his triggers and work through them.

Basil is a sweet and caring dog. It does take him time to warm up but not very long, and once he does he will love you! He does have some quirks though. Link Basil does not like other dogs at all. He is very barrier aggressive when they are walking by his crate. He needs to be in a home where it's only him. He does have a fear of being alone, he doesn't like to be outside by his self at all. But if you are outside with him he is jumping and happy and very playful.

Link has no experience with children and we believe with their higher energy, he would not do well. Link needs routine. A potty as soon as he wakes up and right after breakfast are a must if you don't want an accident. He does love human contact and will let you sit and pet him for hours if you would. Link has a nervous personality and barks at new noises and people.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Timid. Link will bark at strangers. Once he warms up he is a very caring dog.

Other tips and tidbits: Link needs a very experienced owner in a home where he will be the only dog.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. animal.description: Hi! I’m Lana and I’m looking for my Furever Match! My last owner didn’t take good care of me and then left me for dead at the shelter. The shelter said my time was up and I was scared, but thankfully I was rescued. I still don’t know exactly what that means, but I know I’m a lot more happy and not scared anymore! I have some fur missing on my back but it’s growing back thankfully! I’m about 3 years old and only about 25-30lbs. I guess you could say I’m a “itty bitty pocket pittie”. I have never lived inside of a home so I am still learning to potty outside, but I promise I will learn! Unfortunately, I never learned how to live with other dogs so I need to be your only furbaby and hopefully in a home without small children. I currently live with a 3 year old human boy, but I just don’t know how to be gentle with him. I like to play, can you blame me?! I haven’t met any cats yet so I can’t be sure that I would like them.. but you know what I do love?! Snuggles! If you think you’d like to snuggle me furever please email my matchmakers! They are working around the clock to find me my furever match! ??Matchmakers@furevermatch.com

animal.description: Lyla is a lovely, sweet girl who's looking for a special forever home. She was found and rescued on the streets dragging her hind legs, apparently having been hit by a car. Luckily, she was placed in a foster home where she goes to rehab and is making great strides in her recovery. This affectionate, well-mannered girl still cannot walk on her back legs, but she's happy to scoot across the house and backyard, playing with her two dog housemates and doing excited goofy twirling. She loves chewing her stuffed toys and bath time and does well when left in a crate. And she loves being taken for neighborhood rides in her wheelchair. Then she's quite content to snooze and relax near her humans, hoping for the head and face scratches she loves. Lyla is beginning therapy that may improve her ability to walk. In a new forever home, she would need continued care for her injury rehabilitation and diapers for her incontinence. In return, she'll reward her new owners with love and loyalty. She will be forever grateful. Come see if Lyla can be your new best friend!

animal.description:
*On Medical Hold*
Georgia is a 2-year-old Great Dane who arrived at White Kisses 6 months ago. She was in horrible condition. Scared, extremely emaciated, Ehrlichia positive and anemic. She was skin and bones and had no hair on her body from sarcoptic and demodex mange. Her skin was cracked, bleeding and painful to even look at so we can’t even imagine the level of discomfort that she was in. She was also terrified of people.

With much love and care, Georgia is transitioning into a beautiful girl. Her mange is clearing up and she is putting on weight. She is still very scared of people but is slowly starting to trust that not all people are bad – there are some who will love her. As soon as she is ready – both mentally and physically – she will be looking for her forever home.

To follow her story, follow up on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/whitekissesgdr/

animal.description:
FOSTER HOME NEEDED!!!! Meet beautiful Miss Millie… Millie, approximately 2-3 years old, is looking for a home to call her own. Can you tell this sweet face no?
This sweet girl is a lover and is looking for a dog-savvy family to love her back! Millie came to us from a home where she had been improperly trained on an electric fence and was repeatedly being shocked when she would leave the yard. She has overcome many of her issues related to this, but she will require a family with a physical fence or one committed to leash-walking.

Millie would love an active family or one who will take her to doggie daycare to get her energy out. She would do fine as an only dog or with a stable, submissive dog, but no cats. She is also crate-trained.

Millie does have some resource-guarding behaviors. She is currently working with a trainer (who will help transition Millie into her new home), but she will need a family committed to continual management of these behaviors. Due to this, she also needs a home without children.

Millie has a waited too long for her happy forever. Can you be the family she deserves?

At this time, we are unable to process any applications that are outside of the geographic areas listed below:
Greater Louisville, KY (including adjacent southern Indiana)
Greater Lexington, KY
Southern Indiana Counties:  Clark and Floyd
Ohio Counties: Hamilton, Butler, Warren, some areas within Clermont county, Montgomery and Green
Northern KY Counties: Boone, Kenton and Campbell
 
To inquire about a specific dog, we require that you first submit an adoption application.  Visit http://grrand.org/online-adoption-application/  to access our online application.  You do not need to fill out an application for each dog you are interested in learning more about.  Once your application is reviewed a GRRAND volunteer will contact you to begin the process.  Our Adoption Placement Coordinator will work with you to find a dog with the characteristics to best fit your family.

animal.description:
See more pictures of Asher on his Facebook album!

https://www.facebook.com/pg/forgottendogsrescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=3184349371583838

Everyone meet Asher! This guy is a lovable goofball who is really just a puppy at heart. He is an expert snuggler and will keep you laughing.  He has come a long way in his time with us and he is ready to find his forever family!

This big hunk of love was found in late November, 2019, by an Animal Control Officer in Prosser, WA. He was dragging a large chain, but it didn't stop him from jumping in the officer's car and making a new friend! Typical Asher!  Animal control contacted FDR and we agreed to help Asher find a new home. Asher is estimated to be born around December 2017 and he weighs 70 pounds. He’s definitely a bully breed mix, but with his unique coloring and with slightly longer hair than a typical bully breed, we think there’s something else in his mix.

We assume that Asher spent most of his time before coming to us alone on a chain so everything he has encountered since is super-duper exciting! Thankfully he is not fearful of anything new--he is all about trying to play with all the things!  As is typical for a bully breed, Asher has had to learn some impulse control but, he is eager to please his people and has made great strides in learning how to relax and be a good boy.  Asher walks well on a leash but is still working on ignoring all the distractions along the way and will need continued training on his leash manners. 

While he does have tons of energy, he's a laid back pup inside the house who will happily cuddle up on the couch and give kisses.  He loves football games and we are pretty sure he is a Seahawks fan.  He’s very responsive to verbal cues and is a joy to have around with his infectious smile. While his new family will need to be committed to continuing his training, they will be rewarded tenfold with this guy's love and loyalty. Asher is surprisingly gentle with children but, he would do best living in a home with older children given his rambunctious nature and not realizing his own size. 

We think Asher would likely do best as an only dog as he never learned dog language 101 and is lacking some of the social skills to engage in proper play with another dog.  He just gets too excited and doesn’t pay attention to another dog’s cues to back off or take a break. Also, no cats or small animals for Asher, they are just too fun to chase.  

If you are looking for a goofball dog with a huge zest for life, Asher is your pup! Asher is neutered, microchipped and up to date on appropriate vaccines, and his adoption fee is $350.   If interested in adopting, please fill out an application from our website,  www.forgottendogsrescue.com.

Dogs for adoption may be seen by appointment only following an approved application. Proof of completion of an obedience class is required for all dogs following adoption. animal.description:
When most people think of Mesquite, they probably think of a tree they’d rather not have around. They’re not known for their beauty, plus they’re covered in thorns.
I, on the other hand, am known for my beauty and you won’t find a single thorn on me! What you will find is a velvety soft coat topped off by the biggest, cutest pair of ears you’ve ever seen. People tell me I’m goofy and playful. (Flops onto her back for a belly rub at this point?) One of my favorite ways to unwind after a busy day, other than play with my toys, and ride in the car, is to snuggle up and watch movies with you.  And I won’t ever hog the remote, I promise!
Now, before you go thinking I sound absolutely perfect, first let me remind you that perfection is in the eye of the beholder. So I’m looking for a beholder who can look past my one flaw. I don’t really like other dogs or cats. There. I said it. It’s not easy to admit, but that’s the first step to recovery! And they’re actually working with me on that to see if they can change my mind. But in the meantime, I just know there has got to be someone out there who wants me to be their one and only!

This pup can be adopted by going to our web site www.homesforpets.org and filling out one of our applications.

animal.description:
Audrey is a sweet and loving 9-year-old, 60 pound Lab mix who loves to play fetch.  She really loves her humans but prefers not to share her space with other pets. Audrey is best with kids over 12 because smaller kids scare her.  They scare me, too so I don't blame her. 

Audrey is extremely loving and has zero bad habits in the home, but because she doesn't like other dogs, a quiet walking space without other dogs would be best - or yard time with her ball would be just as good. She can be left out in your home for a full workday and she will be there to greet you when you return home.  Audrey is the perfect couch potato who would love to sit with you while you pet on her and binge watch Netflix.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/ then email Debbie@BigFluffyDogs.com.

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier Gender: Female Estimated Date of Birth: January 31, 2012 Size: 50 lbs Location: Kennesaw, GA
RESCUING ROXY (AKA DAISY)
Roxy came into Cobb County Animal Control as a stray on 11/21/2019. As an older gal, she was overlooked, but our friends Lindsay and Alex fell in love and Roxy got her freedom ride on January 30th, 2020. Roxy came down with a pretty serious upper respiratory infection at the shelter, she has a mammary mass, and a loud heart murmur that needs further work up and possibly treatment. We immediately got Roxy to our vet for bloodwork and x-rays. She is going to need an ultrasound as she has a grade 4 heart murmur and her liver enzymes are off. She is also anemic, but we'll be getting her everything she needs.
ABOUT ROXY (AKA DAISY)
Roxy was shy, confused, and a little scared at the shelter, but she is settling into foster care now. She is extremely sweet, calm, and enjoys sleeping on her kuranda bed. The shelter tested her and she seems to do well with other dogs as well. She sits on command and appears to have good leash manners.
*Please check back for updates on this sugar faced lovebug!*
Photo Album of Roxy: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2945616495496497

Princess and Lucky are a bonded pair who must be adopted together. They are generally okay with other dogs. They're playful, loving and affectionate with their family and friends, and self-entertaining, though they prefer to be with their people.

Lucky can be suspicious of new people, so he needs his family to let him know who's a friend. We have a special introduction routine we do when introducing him to someone new. It involves treats and Lucky's favorite Kong jumbler balls, and Lucky knows it means he's meeting a friend. Princess is much more accepting of new people.

Princess and Lucky's ideal home will have a big fenced property that they can roam and protect during the day, and they will be able to come inside, too, especially at night and during inclement weather. They love being outdoors, but they also want to be family pets.

We're looking for someone who understands typical German Shepherd behavior and who will care for them and love them for the rest of their lives!

Interested in adopting or fostering? 

Please fill out our Adoption application: https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24333/generic

OR:

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Luna! I am an energetic 5 yr old spayed female Husky/Cattle Dog Mix. I am fairly independent gal, but once I am comfortable with you I have proven to be quite the affectionate pup! I love me some string cheese and will do just about anything for a frozen Kong, too! My friends at the shelter say I have lots of energy and need a family prepared to take me for some long runs or hikes, and spend lots of time in the fenced-in yard playing ball. Oh, and I wanna mention that I LOVE swimming pools and hoses, so much so that my friends have dubbed me the “dancing queen” because I love to “dance” with the water when the sprinkler is going!

I do enjoy having the spotlight all on me and I love being the center of attention so a home without other dogs or cats is ideal for me. But I’ll do my very best to fill your heart and home with all the love I can give! As for kids? I’ve lived with older kids in the past, so older kids with dog experience may be okay on a case-by-case basis, but I may be too much for younger smaller kids. 

One thing you should know about me is that I love to sing and will readily practice my singing voice whenever I feel like it. But here’s the thing, I plan on trying out for one of those singing competitions on TV so you really can’t blame me. And I have a pretty voice too ;) 

Do you love going for hikes and long runs and spending hours outside? Are you willing to continue taking me to dog training classes so I can keep adding achievements to my resume? If so, I would love you meet you! Call my friends at the Saratoga County Animal Shelter to schedule a meet with me (remember, all dog meets are by appointment only). 518-885-4113. Hope to see you soon! Woof!

animal.description:
Lulu Mae is a super happy-go-lucky and playful 3 year old pit mix!
She loooves other dogs and toys and anything fun. She needs a variety of toys with different shapes and textures as she's obssessed with them. She has only ever chewed on something else when she didn't have multiple toys available.
She is SUPER smart, one of the smartest dogs her fosters have ever met- part of the reason why she's so mischievous. She can master any puzzle almost immediately. 
She's very agile, too, even at 55 pounds. She can jump really high and likes to overcome obstacles. She'd do great in an agility class. She has an active prey drive, so she is not a good fit with cats or small animals. However she loves dogs of all sizes - anywhere from teeny tiny to massive dogs - she loves them all. 
Even with all of her energy and intelligence, she is extremely cuddly and dependent on constant affection. She has a good bit of anxiety, especially separation anxiety, but she does really well as long as she's well exercised and kept on a structured schedule without sudden changes. Other dogs help ground her a lot too, so she is a great fit for a large family pack!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, vaccinated and on heartworm preventative. They live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. Many have basic obedience skills and all have been temperament tested. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, please visit our website to complete an application: http://www.takepawsrescue.org/adoption-form
(please note: app cannot be done on a mobile device)

animal.description:
Jade is a beautiful girl believed to be around 9 years young and is a Shepherd Rottweiler mix. Jade was originally a stray in the Louisville area in 2015 which is how she found her way to rescue where she has been waiting for a home to call her own every since.

Jade has a zealous love for people and is always happy to meet new people. She doesn't believe in 'acting your age' and can still be very over the top when meeting new people wanting to jump, crawl into your lap, etc. She believes she is the perfect size for a lap dog and is an overall love-bug wanting to always be right with you. Jade has spent a fair bit of time around children and as long as they are okay with an abundance of kisses and the attention she supplies there are no worries. Jade has been known to get a bit over-attached and can be inappropriately protective if she doesn't have clear boundaries around her behavior. Don't let her age fool you Jade is a smart, clever, and stubborn girl.

Jade has lived with other dogs her whole time with us and by extension has had to meet a lot of new dogs. She has a very dominant personality when meeting new dogs and can be a jealous attention hog when new dogs are brought into the mix. She understands that this isn't acceptable behavior and when verbally reprimand will stop but if the boundary isn't maintained she is happy to push it. Jade generally has no issue with other medium to large dogs and when she is with a group of dogs she knows she is general unconcerned with what they are doing. Simply put Jade is a pushy queen bee who doesn't like that challenged. Jade would not do well in a home with small dogs or cats.

Although Jade is a 'senior' she is still very energetic and enjoys romping in the woods at her foster home. She is an athletic girl and would do really well in a home with a moderate jogger or a hiker. Jade has a lot of love to give to anyone who is willing to understand her quirks. She is great in the house, loves to ride in the car, and has been waiting a long time for a home to call her own.

If you have any questions about Jade, or would like an adoption application, please email us at tierhavenrescue@gmail.com

animal.description:
Max is a beautiful Shepherd around 2 - 3 years of age who found himself in the shelter after seriously biting someone over a tennis ball. His caregivers at the time where trying to re-home him anyways so they left him at the shelter to be euthanized.

Max is a big, stubborn Shepherd who has clearly been allowed to do as he pleases and bully his way through life. He was recently neutered and as his hormones level out he is realizing that structure isn't so bad however Max requires an experienced German Shepherd handler. Max does well in his foster home and has had no issues meeting new volunteers and friends in his foster home. He is a rambunctious boy who likes a good adventure or stirring up the play group by trying to open the gate - anything for a bit of fun! Max LOVES toys and is a very high drive dog. This would make him great for sport work but also makes him terrible if you think taking toys from him is a good idea. Max does wonderful being redirected onto a new toy and is a sucker for a game of two toy fetch. Max is NOT suitable for a home with children under 13 or children who do not understand respecting the boundaries of a high drive dog.

Max does well with the other Shepherds in his foster home but doesn't really understand roughhousing or playing. He is a bit more stoic during yard time preferring to keep to himself for the most part. Max will interact with the other dogs but simply doesn't care for playing or doing much with the other dogs. Max has NOT been introduced to any dogs under 40 lbs or cats.

To be clear, Max is a wonderful boy in his own regard and is a very smart and eager boy. He is benefiting tremendously from force free training and has some tell-tell habits that speak to a lifetime of negative reinforcement training. If it is your belief that the way to handle a strong willed dog is adverse training this is not the dog - or rescue group - for you. This is not a battle of wills that you will win and it is not worth further damaging such an eager and fun dog so that a handler can exert their dominance.

If you understand how to work with a dogs motivations to help them adjust and learn then Max is a wonderful guy who is going to make a great companion. If you're interested in Max please email Tierhavenrescue@gmail.com or visit tierhaven.rescuegroups.org to view our adoption process.

animal.description: Prancer is a wonderful girl who is 12 years young and very well-traveled. Prancer was originally a stray in Paris where her owners found her as a puppy. They took Prancer in and gave her a loving home and the experience of traveling many countries with them. Unfortunately, when they were asked to relocate to Germany Prancer could not pass customs and they made the decision to surrender her. Prancer has been with us for 3 years now waiting for a new home to call her own. Prancer is loyal to the core and can be a playful and bouncy girl with those she knows but she isn't the type of dog to tolerate being handled by strangers - hence her inability to make it through customs. Prancer believes in mutual respect and earning it. When she enters a new home Prancer can be aloof not wanting to be touched or handled until she has settled in. Overall, Prancer is a no-nonesense type of gal and appreciates a stable environment where she can be a diva. Prancer is not recommended for a home with children as she greatly values her personal space and has no qualms correcting invasions of it herself. Prancer has been living with other dogs and does really well with the other dogs. Again she is a very no-nonsense dog and will tell the younger dogs to leave her alone sometimes but will also play with them at times. Prancer is generally the smallest in her foster homes but despite that she navigates unruly Shepherd foster siblings well. Don't let her age fool you Prancer loves her exercise time and is still an active girl. Prancer has been around cats in the past but not recently. She would need a new cat test and a plan of introduction before she could go to a home with cats. Prancer is above all a very loyal dog and once you have gained her trust and loyalty you couldn't ask for a better dog. Prancer is searching for a home who understands and appreciates her Malinois characteristics and will give her the love she deserves into her golden years. If you have any questions about Prancer, or would like an application, please contact us at Tierhavenrescue@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Macy is an adorable young girl just over 1 year of age who is believed to be a Shepherd Cattle dog mix. Macy came from a rural part of Kentucky where she was live-trapped after being born to a pack of Shepherds that were free-roaming on a farm. Macy had zero human contact prior to being trapped and has been very slow to warm up. She is considered semi-feral at this point and is still overcoming her fears.

Macy prefers to avoid all human contact but has begrudgingly learned how to walk on a leash and tolerate being handled for daily living. Macy is a fear biter and if cornered - such as when she is in her crate and needs to come out - she will lash out in fear. If you move slowly with Macy she settles down and will allow you to handle her but she gets overwhelmed easily when rushed. Macy is going to require extensive ongoing handling, training, and socialization coupled with lots of patience as she continues to grow and bond. Macy has made great progress in her foster home and can be handled by all occupants while she is both on leash and off leash. She enjoys going on hikes around their property - she is still learning to not hate the car which would allow for hiking in new places - and romping in the creek near their yard. Macy does not do well with children which she views as small cattle to be herded - she will nip the back of their legs if left loose with children and will bark at them from her crate. She has been slowly learning to interact while on leash with an 8 year old that visits her foster frequently but would not be recommended for a home with children under 13 years of age. Macy is crate trained and relies on her crate to provide her a safe space to be when she overwhelmed or cannot be supervised. Macy does okay in the house while supervised but does like to chew - she has an expensive taste for cell phones and shoes - and cannot be left loose unattended.

Macy connects with other dogs much better than she does people as a result of her early life in a pack. She does well meeting new dogs and is quick to follow their lead. She loves to romp with the other dogs in her foster home and has learned to meet new foster siblings well. Macy can play rough and uses her smaller size to her advantage taking out the bigger dogs legs while rough housing. She also enjoys chase games as she can run underneath things to hide from the bigger dogs if they get to be too much for her. Macy does live with a cat that she does okay with but she will pester the cat at times and has chased it a couple of times. Macy probably would be great with a cat that is active or likes to run around the house as she is more likely to try to chase it than she is a more sedentary cat.

Macy has a sweet soul and is trying her best to overcome her fears and bond with the people around her. Macy is searching for a home that can provide her a stable environment and ongoing work as she continues to grow beyond her past. Macy will likely take between 3 - 6 months to settle into a new home and is going to require a steady commitment from her future home to her ongoing journey.

If you have a place in your heart and home for Macy please email Tierhavenrescue@gmail.com for an adoption application or visit Tierhaven.rescuegroups.org for more information.

animal.description:
Pepper is a beautiful and wise girl estimated around 9 years young. Pepper came from a rural area of Eastern Kentucky and we do not know her history prior to coming to the shelter. She is a laid back girl though and is looking forward to having a family of her own soon.

Pepper enjoys people but is not an overly affectionate girl. She has her routines, likes them, and appreciates the people that are part of them. She is friendly meeting new people but isn't quick to cuddle. She knows her worth and let's people win her over before getting attached to them. She is a hoot to be around as she is a very confident and sassy girl much of the time. She appreciates a good walk, hanging out in the yard, or nap time depending on the weather. Pepper has been around children 5 years and older and always done well. Pepper has lots of love to give and stories to tell for those who listen. Pepper is starting to explore toys and enjoys playing with balls by herself but hadn't yet figured out the point of fetch.

Pepper is tolerant of other dogs but maintains royal diva status 99% of the time. She doesn't want to play and will let the other dogs know as much. She has been around puppies who are around 18 lbs and was very gentle in delivering the 'you're a pest' message to them. She does live with other dogs but would do best with other laid back adult dogs or as a single dog. Pepper has not been around any dogs under 18 lbs or cats at this time.

Pepper does have multiple fatty lumps on her body that have all been biopsied and examined. The vet advised against removing them as it would be more hassle than benefit to Pepper to undergo surgery. She had a senior blood panel done as well and did not have any concerns.

Pepper is searching for a home that will value her for her wisdom and white muzzle. If you're the home for Pepper email tierhavenrescue@gmail.com for an adoption application or visit tierhaven.rescuegroups.org for FAQs 2/2/21 9:16 AM

animal.description:
Archie is a kind soul who is estimated around 8 years of age and has clearly not had a kind life. Archie was a stray so we do not know his story however his immense fear of leashes and having his neck touched tells a less than nice story.

Archie truly likes people and is a very gentle and loyal boy. He is weary of new people but warms up quickly if you go slowly and respect his boundaries. He loves following his foster family around their house and yard and is never far away. He enjoys being part of the family in a calm, steady sort of way and will go hang out in his crate when overwhelmed. Archie is extremely fearful of leashes and panics when he sees them. It has taken a lot of patience and trust building for him to let his foster family leash him. The reality is he has likely been abused and needs a family that is comfortable taking the time to earn his trust and give him his space until then.

Archie could care less what the other dogs are doing. He doesn't dislike them but doesn't care to play or engage much. He is friendly and appropriate but not playful. He prefers people overall. He seems baffled by toys. Archie has done well during cat testing and his indifference towards cats would likely extend to small dogs as well.

Archie is a gentle soul that has had a rough life and is seeking a calm, patient home that will take the time to earn his trust and show him a better life. If you're the home for Archie please email tierhavenrescue@gmail.com for an adoption application.

animal.description:
Clara is a beautiful female Shepherd estimated around 4 - 5 years of age. Clara was in survival mode when she arrived and has been working to transition out of that and learn to trust people. We do not know her history prior to arriving at that shelter.

Clara has been learning to trust new people and does wonderful meeting new people on leash. She can be timid at first but is quickly won over with a few tasty treats. Once Clara warms up to a new person she behaves like a lap dog - she love cuddle and be right next to you. Overall, she is extremely sweet when given patience and space; however, she doesn't appreciate being rushed or cornered. Clara has been around a volunteers child who is very dog savvy and gives Clara her space. Clara has warmed up to the kiddo and been fine with her every since. We think Clara would do well with older children who are dog savvy but we would not recommend her for a home with younger children or children who don't understand dog boundaries.

Clara does wonderful with the other large dogs in her foster home and she navigates play groups well. She meets other dogs well on leash and is generally well behaved around other medium and large dogs. Clara does have a high prey and level of fixation therefore she is NOT suitable for a home with cats or small dogs. Clara does well supervised in the house and is crated when unsupervised. Clara can be barrier reactive when she is in a new place and will bark along fence lines or in the crate when she sees new people or animals. This behavior is easily redirected and this behavior subsides once she settles into a routine.

Clara is a sweet girl who simply hasn't been given much guidance in life and is a little lost. She is going to need a household with lots of love, patience, and dedication to showing Clara that not only does the world not have to be scary but that she can be a well-mannered dog. Given this guidance Clara is going to make a wonderful and loyal companion. If you have a place in your heart and home for Clara please request an adoption application at Tierhavenrescue@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Ebony is a striking girl around 6 years of age who is a long stay champion with Tier Haven. Ebony came to us as a young girl after being confiscated due to neglect. Ebony was a diamond in the rough and has struggled to find a home of her own since then.

Ebony does great with people and is a playful, social, and energetic girl. She can be reserved with new people at times but warms up quickly and once you're her friend it is for life. Ebony has settled a bit with age but still believes rules were made to be broken and everyone wants to play tug. Ebony has lived with kids over 7 years of age and done well given proper supervision and boundaries for everyone. Ebony loves to creek walk, roll in mud puddles, and generally keep you on your toes. She is also great for grooming and enjoys a good blow dry and brush out to keep her coat nice and healthy.

Ebony is able to coexist with other Shepherds in her foster homes but can be a dominant girl in play groups. She is wicked smart and has a mischievous streak that whispers to her that she should stir everyone up and then get out of there so she can watch them spiral. She can be pushy when meeting new dogs - quietly pestering them when you aren't looking - and does best with a structured introduction with supervision and reinforcement of boundaries. Ebony has lived with other dogs for years and can adjust to a new home with other dogs given proper boundaries. Ebony is NOT suitable for a home with cats or small dogs.

Ebony is searching for a loving home that will channel her energy and intelligence into a job. Ebony is going to require patience, training, and exercise but she has lots of love and laughs to give back.

For an adoption application please email Tierhavenrescue@gmail.com or visit tierhaven.rescuegroups.org for more information on our adoption process

animal.description:
Shiloh is a handsome boy who is estimated around 3 - 4 years of age. Shiloh was completely feral when he arrived with Tier Haven from Hazard, Kentucky. He had not been handled prior to that time and we are unaware of the circumstances surrounding his first few months. Despite being in various foster homes over his years with us Shiloh remains an aloof guy who prefers life on his own terms.

Shiloh is still learning how to trust new people and situations. Shiloh does really well with people from a distance of about 5-7 feet and will linger on the outskirts of interactions but doesn't know what to do when the attention is turned to him. Shiloh will come up and nudge from behind seeking attention but does best when there isn't a big fuss made about it. He has a desire to be around people but doesn't know how to make new friends. Shiloh has learned how to better navigate new situations with each of his foster homes and ultimately does well meeting new people in his foster homes. He has a very fun and playful personality when he is comfortable in a home and is a very well mannered boy. He prefers having a crate as a safe zone but is well behaved loose in the house as well. Shiloh has been around children over 7 years of age semi-regularly and does okay with calmer, more mature children. He gets overwhelmed easily with younger, rambunctious children and would prefer a home with a more settled atmosphere.

Shiloh does great with other dogs and really relies on them for social cues. Shiloh was originally found running with another dog and has always been around other dogs in his time with us. Shiloh loves to romp and run with other dogs and has a very comedic personality in the play yard. Shiloh has been around dogs of all ages and does a great job respecting boundaries the other dogs set and navigating new personalities. Shiloh has been around dogs 15 lbs and up with no concerns. Shiloh has lived with cats off and on throughout his life and generally does well. He will try to play with the cats but is respectful when they tell him to go away. Shiloh would do well adjusting into a new home with other dogs, or cats, that can help him navigate his new environment.

Shiloh is looking for a home with the patience and understanding to help guide his transition into a new family and new adventures. If you have a place in your heart and home for this sweet young boy please email tierhavenrescue@gmail.com for an adoption application.

animal.description:
Zeus is an Owner Surrender who was born August 2013 almost 7 years old.

Zeus has lived with his family since being a puppy and with their little children.   This black with rust markings Doberman has cropped standing ears and a docked tail. He lived with children and got along with his dog sister but not his dog brother.  Both males were neutered but continued to be territorial.  Zeus needs a home free of cats, also best if he is the only male.  Male dogs make him very nervous.

He is crate trained, does not fence jumping or digging holes.  He also has manners, will not jump up on people.  He is described as "gentle and calm" around humans and great with kids.  He will guard children; so it is best that children visit supervised but not live in the home.

Zeus is up to date on vaccines, on prevention - HW Negative.
He is from the Lone Star state and fostered in Texas, now seeking a new family.  


If you're interested in providing a loving forever home for Zeus, please apply at: http://www.dobermanrescuegroup.org/adopt.htm

***********NOTE: We will not answer questions about any dog until we have received a completed application.

Find us on Facebook to see updates and more photos of our Dobermans.
@DobermanRescueGroupInc.

Zeus is available for placement in Texas, Oklahoma, Arkansas, Kansas and Louisiana.

animal.description:
Amy came into rescue with her littermate Meg. These two cuties are very sweet and love attention.  They were found as strays and not reclaimed by the owner.  We estimate they were born in July of 2018.    The girls are very bonded and a home together would be "pyrfect" for them.  We hate to split up families. 
 They are fine with male dogs, selective with female dogs, and are unproven with cats.  We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heart worm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Meg and Amy will be placed as inside pets with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $600 for the pair

animal.description:
*ADOPT ME!*
Gina - 10 years old, located in Virginia
Dog ID#: 200013-P-B-FL
Intake Date: 01/11/2020
Available Date: 03/01/2020 

Gina is a sweet older lady who came from a shelter in Alabama. Not much is known about her life before, but she is definitely used to being in a house. She has been reliably housebroken since the day she arrived in foster care. She gets along fine with her foster brother - she would really love him to play with her, but he doesn't play with other dogs. She pounces and play-bows to no avail, but she hasn't given up yet! We don’t know that she’d have the energy to play for long, but she’s ready to show what she can do. She’s not interested in fetch or playing with us humans. She wouldn’t really be a good "kid’s dog." She’s not much into playing with people or goofing around. She’d be happy with someone to relax with and a dog pal.  She does appreciate a kong with some peanut butter though.

She likes to be with you or see where you are at all times, but not to the point of separation anxiety.  We have left the house and left her uncrated for as long as 7 hours without issue. She also likes her meals to be on time (which is whenever she decides she should have it.) Gina lets you know when she is unhappy with a situation. She moans and groans. If she were a human, it’d be like she was running around saying “Woe is me! Woe is me!” Occasionally, she sounds like Charlie Brown’s teacher. 

She has been going for short walks around the block, but we haven’t really been able to socialize her. She is leery meeting new people and is a bit skittish around new loud things, like trucks. She does fine at the vet's office, but beyond that we haven't had the opportunity for her to meet many other people.

Gina has no concept of privacy and if a door isn’t closed all the way, she’ll shove it open and come on in. She also knows if she puts her nose under the lip on a garbage can lid or dog food container and lifts it up, it will open!  She is sneaky too (well, she tries to be) - say you’re standing in front of an open pantry trying to pick a snack. That offers the perfect opportunity for Gina to come up beside you, grab something off the shelf and wander away. (“If I can get to it, it’s mine!” ~ Gina)

Gina has some of the typical "older-dog" things going on - she's a bit lumpy, although the ones she has had removed were all benign. She is mostly deaf. She still manages to realize anytime you’re in the kitchen without her though!

She had a bunch of bad teeth and the vet removed 19! You’ll need to soak her kibble or feed her soft food. She is a treat grabber. We’re trying to work on “gentle.” We’d definitely have a few notches in our fingers if she did have teeth.  We’re also not sure if she can do stairs. When she walks, her back legs are stiff. We weren’t sure if she could jump, but she managed to get on the couch. She doesn’t reverse very well and will often end up on her butt if she tries to walk backwards. 

Overall, the vet thinks she's in good shape for her age.

Gina loves her people (especially the lady!) and would make a great companion for someone looking for an affectionate older dog with low exercise requirements. She is spayed, up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative and microchipped.

If you think Gina might be the older companion you’ve been looking for, please fill out an application.

Want to learn more about one of the dogs we have up for adoption? Fill out our adoption application (http://www.pointerrescue.org/adopt.html)!!

TRANSPORT AVAILABLE TO APPROVED HOMES! (currently within 600 miles)

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Hi, everyone! My name is Scarlett. I am a sweet,

4-

4.5 yrs. old, Blue Nose Staffordshire Terrier saved by Rescue Ridge from a local NJ shelter. I have learned a great deal here at Rescue Ridge in Monmouth County NJ and the folks here have me set up with a professional trainer where I am learning even more. I know a few commands, take treats and food gently, love to go for walks, car rides, and play in the play yard at the kennel. I am good with large dogs and the folks here have not tested me with small dogs or cats so we are really not sure about that. What they are sure about is that I give wonderful kisses once I get to know you. I am best in an adult home with an experienced owner. I get too excited about my toys but you can correct me to let me know to stop. That is what my trainer has taught me and I am eager to learn and please you. I walk well on a leash but sometimes I want to play with my leash so please do not let me. They really want me to go to a home that is willing to keep up with my great training. If you are willing, then that would be perfect! I keep my kennel very clean and I am housebroken. I really want to go home so please apply to adopt me at rescueridge.com No inquiries, please, without an application. I sure hope to meet you soon so we can have lots of fun together! Please apply to adopt Scarlett at rescueridge.com she is waiting in her kennel in Monmouth County NJ and she is so sad seeing so many other dogs come and go.

Here is my newest video:

https://youtu.be/LjGsN0-mvlk and here is my previous video when she first arrived https://youtu.be/Ogw1Pu-T1Z0

animal.description:
Hello. Cupid called. He wants to tell you that he needs my heart back!

Hi, I'm Gunner! I'm a sweet, middle aged cuddle buddy, looking for an experienced dog snuggler for a lifetime relationship. Unfortunately, in my 7.5 years, I have had my heart broken too many times. Some people don't understand my "attitude", but I'm not really bad! I'm just a bit more cat-like than other dogs, preferring to not be moved from any spot I deem to be mine. But once I am settled in and know that you are the boss, I'll adapt to what you need.

Greatest asset: I am very chill for the most part. I just want to play for a short while, then cuddle and hang out with my human. I'm also the perfect size!

Biggest flaw: I've been described as being a bit "grumpy" when having to move from the spot I am sleeping in. I mean, who wants to be forced to give up their spot?

Theme song: True Colors, Cyndi Lauper

Cat person or dog person?: I am totally cool sharing you with cats, or fellow dogs, as long as those dogs aren't males larger than me. What can I say? I'm quirky.

Kids?: I love em!

Ideal Partner: An experienced dog parent who is willing to take charge and be patient while I learn what they need from me.
animal.name: Gunnery Sergeant

animal.description:
BOXER/BULLY MIX; Sleek white jacket, black oval patch over right eye.  About 50lbs.
ADULT FEMALE; Est DOB: October 2017.
ARRIVAL: January 18, 2020
HISTORY: Riley arrived as a stray at a high kill shelter. When space became an issue, we spoke up for her.
EXTRA NOTE:  Riley has already developed a fan base here.  
No cats or dogs for Riley.

Volunteer Thought: Living the life of Riley?? Well, for Riley her idea of "living the life of Riley AKA a charmed life" would mean giving and receiving love and attention.  As terrific as she is in getting along with humans, one would think her new home is just a tail wag away!   A very well balanced girl, Riley nicely sits when asked and if she is feeling a little more froggy, will run and chase after balls. Since coming to CFC, Riley has made it apparent that an environment surrounded by numerous dogs and without ample one-on-one human interaction like we have here, is simply not for her. When she first arrived here, she would play with other dogs and even happily go for walks with them, but as the months have rolled by, Riley has gotten more and more reactive to other dogs and for this reason, we feel that initially, she needs to be in a home where she is the only pet and with a human who will slowly try to reintroduce her to building relationships with other dogs. A skilled leash walker but perhaps at times a little more strong, Riley seeks and gives affection and would be very much in her element caring for older kids (12+) in her new home. Riley hopes to find a family who will allow her to live the charmed life she so deserves and yearns for. Think you can give this sweet girl a new home and the life of Riley that she so deserves?

Staff Thought: Riley is such a loving sweetheart.  She can be a little strong on the leash like a girl on a mission but will nicely stop when I ask for her attention.  I was successful in redirecting her with a sit, which she does know and pretty much does whenever I give her the command.   Once in the arena, she was curious and would amble around, but didn’t show too much of an interest in toys.  Again, I could get her attention when I called for her.  If I sat down, she would come and check in, and climbed up on the bench so she could better access my lap.  It started raining, so I didn’t keep her out too long, but spent some time loving on her in her pen.  I started giving her some butt scratches and body rubs which she loved, and she in-turn started just rubbing her body all over mine giving me a full-body snuggle, which was super  adorable.  I think that she is a calm, gentle-natured girl – up for walks and adventure, but also content to just be snuggled-up next to her human.

**If you are reading this post, this pet is still available for adoption. Please read the entire post below on how to apply, and before calling or emailing!**

Papi is a very special 12lb  6-year old Chihuahua who is our longest canine resident at the AWS shelter. He has been with us 270 days. We don’t know what kind of life Papi had before he was rescued from a high-kill shelter in Texas, but it was obviously a pretty bad one. Papi did not like to even be touched when he first arrived. After much love and patience, Papi is now very sweet and loving with people he knows. He actually seeks out attention and human touch. Papi has even learned to sit and shake. He is very treat motivated. Papi DOES NOT like other dogs or cats. This has not changed while being with us. So in his forever home, he must be the only pet. His forever home should also be quiet, patient, and adult only. He would be the perfect companion for an older, single person who is still active, as Papi loves his walks! In order to adopt Papi, you will have to visit and spend time with him until he is comfortable with you. Once that happens, he will be your loyal and loving best friend.  Papi has been vet checked, dewormed, heartworm tested negative, fully vaccinated and neutered.  ADOPTION FEE $200

If this is up, Papi is still available. He is here in our facility.
Please fill out an application online or at the facility.
animalwelfaresociety.net

***DUE TO COVID, WE ARE OPEN BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. NO WALK-INS WILL BE ACCEPTED!

IN ORDER TO ADOPT,
YOU MUST HAVE AN APPROVED APPLICATION PRIOR TO COMING IN TO MEET AND SPEND TIME WITH A PET. OUR ONLINE APPLICATION CAN BE FOUND ON OUR WEBSITE: WWW.ANIMALWELFARESOCIETY.NET. ONCE APPROVED, WE WILL CONTACT YOU TO SET UP AN APPT. UNFORTUNATELY, WE CANNOT CONTACT EVERY APPLICANT, AS WE SOMETIMES RECEIVE OVER 100 APPS FOR ONE PET!

THANK YOU FOR YOUR UNDERSTANDING AND COOPERATION.***

animal.description:
Description:
Rosie is 20 pounds of pure sweetness.  Best guess on breed would be Chihuahua with some herding dog mixed in there and possibly some sort of rare black fox - who knows!  She is around 3.5 years old.  Rosie is a cutie and she knows it - she loves any and all of the attention she can get!  She also loves her doggie foster brother even though he's a grumpy old man who is generally indifferent towards her - she is determined that he will learn to romp and play with her!  She'd love a doggie sibling to play with, but would also be fine having her forever family all to herself.  She's a great cuddle buddy on the couch (although she might give you a new gentle nudges when she's decided she needs more pets), but is also excited to go out for walks and sniff around the neighborhood.  Rosie is crate trained and attends doggie daycare with her canine friends, but needs a quieter home without children.

Animals can be viewed by appointment only. We ask that you review our adoption information AND fill out an adoption application prior to setting an appointment so we have all your information and you understand our adoption procedures - you can do so online here.     

Please feel free to email us or call us anytime for additional information on any of our animals - info@mcprescue.org or 312-388-3928. Our typical adoption fee varies based on the age of the dog at the time of rescue: Under the age of 1 years old is $500; 1-5 years old is $400; over the age of 5 is $300. Fees include vaccinations, microchip, deworming and other vetting as needed. Our adoption process includes an application, reference check and home visit.

animal.description:
This big handsome boy is Frosty and he is a gem! Frosty is a sweet boy, good with other dogs and cats, too. He really likes people and is a really friendly guy. Frosty came into rescue after he was found injured lying under someone’s porch and went unclaimed. He had some very deep puncture wounds but he has been treated at the vets office and he is healing up nicely now. They appeared to be bite marks but thankfully he is on the mend. Frosty walks well on leash and he is a bouncy happy guy - always happy to see his human or dog pals :) He would love a great home of his own and a family to love him. Frosty may have had a rough start but he has turned out to be such a great dog. He is currently in boarding sure could use a home or foster home to go to. We just love this big happy boy and so will you. We are not sure what his life was like before he came to rescue. Not sure if he lived indoors or out but he adores people so he should do just fine with a kind family to teach him all he needs to know. Please consider making this big happy boy a part of your family!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Ross was surrender to a shelter when his elderly owner passed away.  He is looking for a quiet, one person home.  Ross can be picky about his doggie friends and he is not a fan of cats therefore he would do best as an only pet. He is still playful, sometimes a little strong on a leash, but most times not too bad.  This gorgeous boy is very loyal, protective of his person, very affectionate, and loves belly rubs.  Ross is sometimes a little strong on a leash but most times not too bad.  Ross very much wants to have someone of his own to love.  Ross is 7 years old and 121 pounds (yes you read it right - 121 lbs). 
Ross would do best in a home with the following criteria:
-No kids, other dogs/cats/pets
-One adult preferred 
-Experienced dog owner
-Low foot traffic home (non active home without lots of people coming in and out)

Please understand that we are an animal shelter and thus unable to say whether the dogs are housebroken as they are not in homes.

If you are interested in adopting, we encourage you to please submit an application on our website today so that we can try and process and pre-approve any potential adopters prior to our next adoption event.

PLEASE USE THIS LINK TO SUBMIT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION. WE ONLY ACCEPT ADOPTION APPLICATIONS THROUGH OUR WEBSITE. ANY OTHERS WILL NOT BE PROCESSED.
Application link here: http://www.oscaranimalrescue.org/oscar-1-application.html

Adoption Process:
1.Fill out an application
2.Meet & Greet
3.Adoption contract & adoption fee
Ross' adoption fee is $100. This covers all age-appropriate shots, vetting & microchipping.

**If you are coming to an adoption event to see a certain dog/cat, please email ahead of time to make sure that dog/cat will be there that day. Please email 1-2 days before the event, as some animals are placed during the week and our list is constantly changing.
For a list of upcoming pet adoption events go to: www.OscarAnimalRescue.org

animal.description:
Hi.  My name is Flash. I'm a friendly 5-6 yr. old dalmatian labrador retriever mix who ended up in the East Valley LA City shelter.  Luckily, Rescue saw me on a video of playing dogs and knew i would make a fantastic dog for some dog loving family. I got my new name, Flash, because I was so very fast in the video.  Now I am living in a kennel in Newport Beach.  I was a bit shy when i first came in (as you can see from my sad sack photos) but now i'm enjoying playing in the yard, going on my daily walk and playing with my friends.  The walkers here are teaching me my leash manners and how to sit for treats, but i do need an experienced dog owner with lots of patience as I've had no training and am a strong bodied girl.  I also do like all of the attention when my people are around so I would be best as an only dog.  I am spayed, vaccinated and microchipped so I am ready to go anytime you call for me.  I am so looking forward to  meeting my new family .. could it be yours?

If you are interested in meeting me, please contact Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc. by email .  To ensure I would be a good fit for you and your family, Rescue requires completion of an adoption questionnaire but once submitted and approved, arrangements can be quickly made for you and your family to come meet me at the kennel.  I love making new friends so please do contact Rescue and ask about me, Flash, as soon as you can.

To learn more about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., a 501c3 non-profit charity, and to see all of our available dogs, please visit our website at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit us on facebook at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love seeing posts and photos of life with your spotty friends so please, keep them coming.  Thanks!
