animal.description:
Meet Miss Thea Queen! This beautiful girl has been with us at Wanderer's for quite some time now, and by "quite some time we mean she just passed 400 days as being a resident here at the shelter. 
Why? Well, that's a great question with a complex answer. 
Like MOST dogs Thea is absolutely terrified, which more then likely is presented as aggression when inside her kennel. The primary reason for this is because her kennel is HER HOME. She is a young dog whose life prior to the shelter we have no knowledge of; meaning for all we know she could have escaped an inadequate living environment, OR she could have possibly had a great home. We'll never know, but that's okay!
With the being said, imagine being in a foreign place, your new living quarters doesn't have windows and only one way out that's locked and requires thumbs to open (now imagine being a dog for that part). Then imagine having to use the restroom but being unable to actually use the restroom. That's what it's like in the minds of most shelter dogs, you'd be a wreck too. Even though Thea is a Queen she can be a bit dramatic when meeting new people. Initially she can become defensive, definitely scared, and she'll even cower in the back end of her kennel. Maybe she'll let out a bark or 4 that doesn't show you who she actually is, what she's saying is "HEY! The Queen doesn't know you!!! 
Our Thea here has required a bit of work to get her to where she is right now, we couldn't be more proud of her and how far she's come! After spending lots and lots of quality time with Thea we've learned so many wonderful things about her that truly did shock us! She is STRONG, but eager with a secret submissive side. She just absolutely loves laying out in the grass, all splayed out like a frog, you can truly see the happiness in her facial expression and the bliss in her eyes, it's truly a sight to see. Another fan favorite of Theas is WATER, she could spend all day in the kiddy pools, she'll wade in the water and even lay in it for an impressive amount of time too. It usually takes place after she's had an intense tug-o-war match, or fetch! She fancy's both, but her absolute favorite toys are squeaky stuffed animals, any species she doesn't have a preference, as long as she can rip it to shreds and show them who the real Queen is she's happy. You'd think she would have slipped a disk or given herself whiplash with how intensely she shakes her head back and forth.
Theas adopter is required to continue her current obedience training. They'll need to have a very clear understanding of what it takes to properly care for her. Consistency is key for Theas success. It's highly suggested that her new owner is a single male, Thea responds impressively well to the depth of a mans voice and seemed to start obeying commands much quicker opposed to female handlers. Although it's not impossible for a women to gain her trust. 
Getting to know Thea will also require and consist of multiple visits to the shelter to guarantee a perfect fit. Thea is full of excitement and enthusiasm for every possible adventure! Will you be joining our Queen as her King? Guess you'll have to come and meet her for yourself! By appointment only, of course, being royalty and all.

animal.description:
Serabi is a beautiful and petite little girl weighing in around 12ish pounds, This sweet and scared little mama needs a very special family to help show her that the world of being spoiled and loved is not a bad one.  Serabi is NOT aggressive at all, but she is very fearful and needs someone with patience. We are requiring the future adopter to have another dog as she would do best in a home with a doggie (or a couple doggie) companions.  Serabi tries to run and hide, and only knows living as a stray. She  had a few litters on the street and lived under the same house for years but the people that lived there never got close to her or tried to socialize her. Thankfully, we were finally able to trap Serabi so that she can now live a wonderful and safe life going forward. Serabi requires a very secure fenced yard as she is terrified of the leash and will look for the smallest hole to try and escape. Serabi would do best in a home with another dog and children over the age of 10 as she is very timid and needs to be a home where they understand her.  We are hoping with patience, time and TLC Serabi will learn to not be so afraid of her new world. 

To apply to adopt Serabi, please visit www.snarrnortheast.org

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, so there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $425 for adults / Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. All dogs are given monthly flea/tick preventative, monthly heartworm preventative, and are dewormed regularly. Dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are microchipped. Adoption fee is $50. Home visit and vet reference required. Applications can be put in online at http://www.troyanimalrescueproject.org/adopt.php or in person at our rescue center.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description:
RODEO IS WELL BEHAVED AROUND OTHER DOGS ON-LEASH BUT BECAUSE OF HIS SIZE AND STRENGTH, WE FEEL HE WOULD BE BEST AS THE ONLY PET IN THE HOME. APPLICANTS MUST LIVE IN THE CITY OF LOS ANGELES IN AN ADULT-ONLY HOME (NO APARTMENTS) WITH A  PRIVATE YARD.

RODEO is the definition of a Rhinestone Cowboy! Not only does he have flashy good looks but his DNA results prove that he is quite a unique gem. Like many rescue dogs, his life has been off to a bit of a sad start. He was surrendered to the East Valley Animal Shelter because his family was moving to a place that didn’t allow dogs. Like the song says, "You're ridin' the RESCUE TRAIN that's takin' the long way." We know this buckaroo is destined for greatness and a wonderful FURever home! 

At 85 pounds and a year old Rodeo is still growing. Because of his grand stature, he would require a home with a yard (NOT AN APARTMENT), a big dog lover with strong handling experience and a structured environment. Mostly comprised of Great Pyrenees, he has the potential to be protective of his family. Australian Cattle Dog and Border Collie as secondary breeds, mean someone familiar and knowledgeable with herding breeds would be highly recommended. 

Rodeo is neutered, vaccinated and microchipped and whoever is lucky enough to adopt this rooty tooty cowboy will get an in-home dog training lesson as part of his adoption. Now that’s something to YEE-HAW about!

--
If you are interested in adopting RODEO please go to www.TheRescueTrain.org and fill out our online adoption application on the Adopt A Dog page. Applications are required PRIOR to meeting one of our animals and are used to set up a safe and successful adoption.

Please don't be shy and answer the questions thoroughly. To learn more about our entire process please visit www.therescuetrain.org and click on the Adopt A Dog page or email us at info@therescuetrain.org.

*APPLICANT MUST BE AT LEAST 21 YEARS OLD*
*APPLICANT MUST LIVE IN THE CITY OF LOS ANGELES*

PLEASE NOTE: WE DO NOT OWN A FACILITY. Our animals are in private foster homes. If you are interested in adopting one of our animals please fill out our online application. Or check our mobile adoption schedule on our home page.

animal.description:
Name: Carmen
Age: 1 1/2 years old
No small children, dogs or small pets
Review Malinois adoption requirements below

 Carmen is exactly what you should expect of a 2-3 year old Belgian Malinois. She has endless amounts of energy and genius level intelligence. She will need someone who can give her a LOT of physical and mental exercise. She loves attention and will need loads of it. Someone wanting to adopt Carmen will need to be able to meet all of her breed’s specific demands.

Carmen will need:
-3-5 hours of exercise a day
-Daily training for mental stimulation
-No small children in the household
-No other dogs unless the handler is experienced with Malinois dogs living with other dogs
-No cats or small pets in the household
-A strong, active handler
-Someone who has experience with Malinois dogs
If you can meet these requirements for Carmen then she will be one of the sweetest, most loyal,  and loving companions you can find.

If you can give Carmen an indoor forever home, please fill out our online application on our website at http://www.savingpawsrescueaz.com/adoption-form/    We will only schedule meet and greets with an approved application. We are an all-volunteer organization.  It may take a couple of days to process an application and complete reference checks.  Thank you for your interest in saving a life!

                              *****Belgian Malinois Adoption requirements*****

The dog you have selected is a Belgian Malinois.  This is a breed that has very specific needs for an adoptive home.  Because of their need for a high level of exercise, both mentally and physically and their need for ongoing training, only applicants with demonstrated owner/handler experience with this breed will be considered.  The vast majority of them are not best suited as family pets, but in homes with experienced handlers knowledgeable of their needs and breed characteristics.  We will not place in homes with small children or small dogs/cats.  Must be previous owner/handler to be considered

animal.description:
Name: Kane
Age: 4 years
Medical - special food diet - salmon kibble; allergies
No small children, other dogs or cats  

Volunteer favorite big boy Kane is ready and waiting for his forever home! You may remember Kane came to us about a year ago from a high-kill shelter in California. He is approximately four years old and likely spent most of his life as an outdoor dog. He was fortunate enough to go for a little staycation with one of our volunteers recently. She reports: “Kane is a very good dog! This big boy loves to cuddle on the couch and cannot get enough belly rubs. He is mostly well mannered but can sometimes be a lot to handle in a puppylike way. Kane is mouthy when he gets excited but is easily redirected. Since being in a house is new for him, he’s very curious and wants to be in the middle of everything. He may run off with a shoe or swipe something out of the fridge, but he is good about giving things back. He’s a good boy at night, either sleeping on the bed or the floor nearby. Kane is a hungry boy, very food motivated, and needs to learn some manners around people food. Kane is not destructive in the house, though he will destroy toys when he gets excited. He was left alone in the house for several hours without issue. Overall Kane is a big sweetheart who wants to please and just needs some direction. Fun fact – he loves to eat ice cubes!” 
Kane will require a strong handler to help him with his leash skills. Since he is so large, he should not be in a home with small children. Additionally, he should be the only pet in the house. His skin issues are still healing and of course SPR will always be available to help any future foster or adopter until he is fully healed.

Kane is going to  take a dedicated adopter who wants to be a part of his journey.  Are you up for the challenge? 

If you can give Kane an indoor forever home, please fill out our online application on our website at http://www.savingpawsrescueaz.com/adoption-form/  

 We will only schedule meet and greets with an approved application. We are an all-volunteer organization.  It may take a couple of days to process an application and complete reference checks.

Thank you for your interest in saving the life of a dog.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Riley and I’m a toy fox terrier who lived in a puppy mill for 6 1/2 years, where I was forced to live in a cage and have tons of puppies. But then I was rescued and adopted by my loving mom. Unfortunately, my mom is having some health issues and I’m staying at the vet right now until I can find another home where I’ll be just as loved. TFTR is helping me find just the right family!

I turned 13 in November, so I’d love a home where I can have lots of love, snuggle in comfy beds, and hang out with you!

I have a very special walk because I had 2 broken bones in the puppy mill and no one took care of me, so my legs didn’t get a chance to heal the way they were supposed to. But I still get around just fine and only need pain meds every now and then to help me feel better.

I get along well with other dogs, but I am a little shy with people until I have a chance to get to know you. I had a doggie door in my last home, so I may need some help learning how to potty in the right place if you don’t have one at your home!

I’m located in Muskogee, OK and am up to date on my shots, am heartworm negative, and spayed. Transport is possible to surrounding areas like MO, TX, AR, and KS!

animal.description:
Hi all! I’m Toaster! My friends call me Toast for short. I’m not really sure how I got my name. Although the more that I think about it, maybe it’s because when you meet me, I will make your heart all warm and toasty? Yes, I think maybe that HAS to be it! Mystery solved! Although since I solve mysteries so well, maybe I should have been named Scooby Doo!

Anyhow, before I get distracted, let me tell you some things about me. I’m about 5 years old and they think I’m a mastiff or Cane Corso mix. So I’m kind of a big guy! But that doesn’t mean I have a big head! I mean, PHYSICALLY I do have a big head. What I mean is I don’t have a big head like a big ego. Gosh, sometimes it’s difficult to communicate in human. 

Really, I’m just a happy guy, who is extremely curious about new things. I love going on walks and checking everything out with my nose. I really love checking out storm drains and sewers. I mean, you never know what might be living in them! I seem to like to meet new people on my walks, too. I usually walk quite nicely on the leash unless I see something I really want to check out, and then I forget not to pull. It’s hard to remember to walk nicely when you seek something really interesting! But I’m more than happy to work on my leash manners a bit. 

I absolutely love riding in the car, and I am VERY well behaved riding in the car. I also love to play with toys like tennis balls and stuffies. I will admit, I sometimes think I’m the size of a puppy and I often get bouncy like a puppy! And I’ve been known to do zoomies when I get really excited. It seems to make everyone laugh. And I sure like making people laugh. I’ve been known to give big slurpy kisses and to “hug” people when I think they need it. So I hope you like kisses and hugs.

I like when humans pet me, but I much prefer booty scratches to head scratches. (I’ll let you in on a little secret; many dogs prefer that!) I think there’s almost nothing as good as a good booty scratch. Except maybe car rides. 
I’m pretty good at sitting when asked, and I’m learning new things. I just haven’t had a whole lot of training with such requests, but I am receiving some now and I love to learn! Especially when learning is accompanied by some tasty treats!

I am NOT a fan of cats. Well, I mean I AM a fan of CHASING cats, but that activity seems to be frowned upon. So I need a home without cats. In fact, I'd like to be your one and only pet, if you don't mind.  

If you are interested in making your heart feel all Toasty, or want to find out more about me, please call/text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387.


INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET? Fill out an Adoption Application now! Appointments can also be made to meet a pet by calling us at 913-671-PETS (913-671-7387).  

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
Prior to adoption, our animals are: 
**Tested for diseases 
**Vaccinated 
**Spayed/neutered 
**Microchipped 

NO COST adoptions with an encouraged donation are accepted. 

The Pet Connection also offers adopters a FREE veterinary examination and a medical care support plan for 60 days after adoption, as well as lifetime behavioral training, safe sanctuary for pets returned in emergency situations, extensive assistance with lost and found pets, and other expert pet services in a variety of areas, including pet selection, behavioral issues, general training, nutrition, and transition to adoptive homes.

Please visit our website at www.thepetconnection.org for more information about The Pet Connection and for a full listing of our available pets, 

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 if you can foster, adopt, or sponsor a special needs dog or cat! 

The Pet Connection is a membership organization operating a no-kill adoption center located at 417 N Rawhide Suite H, Olathe, KS 66061.

animal.description:
Meet Gabi. She's a 2-1/2-year-old Pit mix who is beautiful, fun, and ready for you to take her home.  Gabi is a beautiful onyx black color with an adorable white chest. She's sexy and she knows it!

Gabi is young and full of energy. She would love a home with a fenced-in yard and another dog to rough and tumble with.  She has been fine with every dog we have introduced her to - big, small, grumpy, and happy. She does best with dogs of similar size (she's about 70 lbs) and energy level. She also would be fine as an only dog as long as she gets plenty of exercise.

Gabi will need time to adjust to her new humans and she has a touch of stranger danger, but she's been through extensive training to help build her confidence.  Gabi is super intelligent and really wants to please her humans so she would be a great dog for someone interested in ongoing training exercises.

She would be fine with sturdy kids over the age of 12 who are respectful of the dogs they share their home with.  She walks best on a harness, she is housetrained and just wants love, pets, and treats.

Gabi is a no cat kind of gal. She is way too interested in them, and when they hiss or paw at her, it's game on. 

This pretty gal is currently in Nashville, and can travel anywhere we place dogs and we would even consider a foster-to-adopt depending on your location. If you lead an active lifestyle, this is the gal for you. She is fun, lovely, soft and beautiful and will be the best companion you could ask for. To foster or adopt this amazing girl, please visit our website at www.bigfluffydogs.com, click on Foster or Adopt and fill out the required form found there for her. Once that's complete, please email debbie@bigfluffydogs.com for more information on this beautiful girl.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

Meno is about 2 years old and is BLIND,  He is tiny at only 7 pounds. He will need a home without stairs and no children under 8 years old. He does like to play with dogs, so another small dog would be great for him.  Please know large dogs pose a risk to little Meno as he can't see to get out of their way so a home without large dogs is preferred.  Meno also enjoys being in your lap and being carried around.

He needs a home where someone is home with him, or can take him to work and not be left crated all day alone.
He is potty trained as long as you pay attention to his cues. 

Meno will need  a few visits with any potential adopter before going home with someone as he needs to feel secure. This is a must!
He is crate and puppy pen trained. Does good on a leash. Good on car rides.

A fence is required! Please research caring for a blind dog before applying.
Please make sure you meet the requirements before applying for this sweet boy.



If you are interested in Meno please fill out an application at fuzzballrescue.com.  We are an all volunteer organization and it can take a while to go through applications and receive a call from us.

Applications are at fuzzballrescue.com under forms.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.All of the animals posted on our site have been temperament tested. While not all are in the immediate area, once we have processed and approved your application, we will move the dog to our adoptive area for you to meet, greet and hopefully adopt. Sometimes we will have more than one application on a dog. That does not mean it automatically goes to another family but you should be aware of the fact that until you are approved and set up for the meet/greet.. the dog could get adopted by another applicant.NOTE- MICHELLE IS LISTED AS A COURTESY FOR ANOTHER RESCUE ORGANIZATION. PLEASE SEE CONTACT INFO BELOW.Have you always dreamed of having a beautiful girl what you can dress in frilly things? Now you can impress your friends with a pitbull adorned in bows and lace! Michelle is a 6-8 year old pitbull terrier who weighs about 60 pounds. She is a quirky, smart and fun girl who knows what she likes....and doesn't! Michelle wants to be your only child, watch tv on your couch, and look out your window to see what she can see! She has plenty of energy to strut around the neighborhood making you look good and is calm enough to snuggle up for a weekend of Netflix and chill! She is crate trained and house trained and has excellent indoor manners!A reduced adoption fee of $100 does apply for Michelle, our seniors, special medical and behavioral needs dogs and other 'slow to adopt' dogs!Augusta Dog Adoptions is an all- volunteer, foster- based rescue. We take applications online and are scheduling individual adoptions in the Waynesboro, VA area during the pandemic. A $175.00 adoption fee ($300 for puppies under 6 months old) helps us take care of all the dogs we rescue. All dogs are spayed/neutered, tested for heartworm and tick borne diseases (if old enough), microchipped, and vaccinated for rabies (if old enough), distemper/parvo and bordetella. They are also treated for internal and external parasites. Many dogs also receive extensive medical care such as dental work and major surgeries. For more information and to apply to adopt, please visit www.augustadogadoptions.orgIf you google our address, you will be directed to Richmond. That is NOT our adoption event location.

animal.description:
~ THIS IS A COURTESY POST ~ DO NOT CONTACT MASSPAWS ~ 
Please email the shelter at: adoption@popememorialcvhs.org and be sure to tell them ARK sent you!  

 Molly is a 4-year old, 58-pound female hound mix located in Dover, NH. She is a very sweet, active, and cuddly young lady but struggles from fear and stress caused by a life of change and uncertainty. We have more information about Molly’s past that may help her find the right adopter and environment. 

Molly is best-suited for a rural home in a low-traffic area. She will make a nice addition to a quiet family consisting of adults only. No cats, kids, or regular visitors. Molly gets along great with most dogs, but at times prefers to be the alpha depending on the other dog’s personality. Molly would enjoy having a compatible dog sibling. Her favorite pastimes are playing, cuddling and calling dibs on the coziest spot in the house. 

In 2017, Molly originally came to Pope Memorial Humane Society in 2017 from a southern shelter. She was adopted out twice but returned and has been back since June 2019. The first adoption didn’t work out because the adopters reported that Molly had behavioral issues and they did not trust her. There is no record of details, but there was no report of biting. The second adoption was to a couple with a dog. They had her well over a year before returning her because she did not do well with new people coming to the house, especially their grandchildren. They felt she was not safe to have around the children. 

For the past year as a shelter dog, Molly has shown fear aggression and defensive behaviors towards new people. There have been several incidents with the public sticking their hands in her kennel and she has bitten them causing puncture wounds. This is due to her fear of a people reaching over her as she does not trust strangers.  

For the last several months, she has become more fearful of meeting new people so the shelter’s trainer recommended muzzle training. She now meets people wearing a basket muzzle. She would need to meet an interested adopter many, many times as she tends to not get along with people on the first or second introduction. The shelter staff agree she is worth every bit of extra time and patience. Once comfortable, the playful lovable girl shines through. 

In her new home, Molly would need to continue her training and work on her confidence and trust with people. This will be a lifelong commitment and may need constant management. She would not be a good candidate for large gatherings, doggie daycare, etc. She requires a quiet, calm home to be successful and feel safe. Outside of the shelter and once adjusted, behavior modification and training should be much more effective. 

Please email the shelter at: adoption@popememorialcvhs.org and be sure to tell them ARK sent you!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Gracie (as in amazing Grace!) and I am a 2 yr old double merle Aussie mix.  Double merle refers to a genetic condition that occurs when two blue merle dogs are bred together.  The condition sometimes causes deafness and sometimes causes blindness and sometimes causes both.  I am deaf and visually impaired-- I can see light and shadows.  Some people may be put off by my so called disabilities; but I sure don't let my disabilities stop me!  I navigate the world with my nose and sense of smell.  I LOVE people, other dogs, playing outside and chewing up stuffed toys (and my dog bed).  My foster mom says I am a wonderful dancer--when outside in the back yard  I often break out into a joyful choreography of jumps, leaps and spins! A home with a fenced yard is must for me...not only to make me happy but to keep me safe.   I am spayed, up-to-date on vaccinations,  house-broken, crate-trained and beginning to learn touch training.   If you are interested in meeting me, please contact kathie@herdingahven.org

This is beautiful Lilly Bloom with her cream and white coat. She is approximately 4 years old and weighs about 35 lb. She appears to be a small Staffordshire terrier. Lilly needs a home with a fenced yard and a pet parent who can make sure she is exercised regularly. She is a sweet strong girl, but does not get along with other animals. She is loving and is also good with children, but needs an only-pet home.Lilly is spayed, UTD on vaccines, heart worm negative and microchipped. To find out more about Lilly Bloom, call her foster mom, Sharon, at 865-255-5567. Lilly's adoption fee is $175.00 She is located in Knoxville, TN and we will help with transport to her new family. The first step is always an application found at: www.bostonterriertn.org

NOTE: Submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston, since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.

Please use the foster momma or dad's contact information above for questions.
The process always begins with an application which can be found at The Boston Terrier Rescue of East Tennessee website
Note that in most cases, we do not adopt to families with small children, e.g., 'under 6,' as a precaution to the child's safety and the dog's safety. In some cases with larger Boston mixes or other dogs, we do make exceptions. Please ask the foster momma.
We prefer to place dogs within driving distance of where they are being fostered. If someone from outside the local area is approved for adoption, they must be willing to personally drive/fly to get the dog. The East Coast division (NC/SC/VA/MD/DC) does have special transport capabilties for their kids. Ask them.
Also, submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you. 1/31/21 2:42 PM

Bear-Bear is adorably short and super animated. But the best part of Bear-Bear is that once he connects with you, he will bless you with so many gifts of unconditional love. The way he looks at you with his expressive eyes. His bouncy, hoppy run when he is excited to see you or wrestle with you. The way he not-so-gracefully plops down into a sploot on the grass after his walk. His side licks that never make contact on your face as he is staring into your eyes. His piggy snorts that make you giggle, especially on a rough day. When he is sleeping, and all of sudden he starts barking and moving his legs wildly. Never waking up unless you gently rub his back for which he will look at you with one eye, and quickly fall back to sleep. Or, when you hug him, and he feels like a soft teddy bear. The longer he lives with you, the more he will open himself up to you. You will eventually ask yourself, why wasn't he in my life sooner.

animal.description:
BETTY BOOP...
Meet this sweet girl, Betty Boop. I call her Boop Boop some times. She is a doll!!! A female 3-4 year old Mastiff/Boxer mix. She is good with other dogs and just a true sweetheart. She is past that hyper puppy stage and pretty mellow. She just wants to kick back on the couch and cuddle with you while you binge watch your favorite show. 
Betty does have a couple issues...she is heartworm positive. She is currently on monthly heartworm prevention and we will retest her in 6 months even if adopted. She also can be an escape artist. She will climb out of the yard if she wants to be with you.  She can and will escape a wire crate if scared or anxious, which thunderstorms scare her. So, Betty truly needs a home where someone is home almost all the time. Someone retired or someone that can take Betty with them when they travel. 
Betty is a beautiful girl and a sweetheart. She is housetrained and crate trained. She is a hefty girl at 74 lbs.   Her adoption fee is $95, includes her spay, deworming, vaccinations, flea/tick control and microchip. Apply online at www.arlorescue.org
Help us find Betty the perfect home and share!

animal.description:
(Version française disponible ici: 
https://www.sitwithme.ca/fr/dogs/jakk/) 


Jakk
American Pit Bull Terrier
3-4 Years
Male

Dogs: Possibly, with the right dog - female only
Cats: No, thank you.
Kids: 12+
Housing Type: Detached or country homes only
Fenced Yard: Required - special consideration will be given to country homes
Special: Jakk is fostered near Ottawa/Gatineau and needs at least 2 meet and greets near his foster home prior to placement.  We are ONLY considering homes within 3 hours of Ottawa who are willing to travel here for these meet and greets.  

Jakk will need a home in areas with breed neutral laws. At this time he needs to find his forever home outside of Ontario.

Meet the very handsome Jakk!! This fit and trim boy is a wicked amount of fun. He absolutely adores playing in his fenced-in yard with his foster family. He loves playing with balls, sticks and anything else he can find. Jakk also loves to go on forest hikes, and he is rather easy to run with a back belt and bungee line.

Jakk likes to always hold a toy in his mouth and will trade his toy for cookies with ease. It is very endearing so see him carry his stuffy around. Jakk can be a bit intense and has worked very hard with his foster home to always offer a controlled behavior like ‘sit’ and waiting for a release before being let out of his crate or to go out the doors. Jakk is looking for a family that wants to continue working on impulse control, he is a very smart boy but had a tough start without a lot of learning how to be calm and wait for what he wants.

Jakk is crate trained but requires an indestructible crate. In this crate he is fine for a typical work day on his own. He is good more or less all the time, but he is powerful and if he wants out it does not take much for him to destroy a normal crate. He does settle down quickly and sleeps well in his crate. Jakk is also house trained.

Jakk has lived with another dog in the past and could likely live with another laid back, female pooch. Jakk likes to chase and sometimes "taste" the kitties, so no cats in his forever home please! Due to Jakk's size, energy and small quirks, a home with older children is best.

Jakk is very food motivated and will work very hard to earn his treats! He likes routine and structure and will do best in a home that will provide a regular structured day for him.

If you are looking for the most handsome good boi that is ready to be your one and only, apply for him at www.sitwitme.ca/dogs/jakk

animal.description:
DaisyJane is a senior lady who came to BHRG with her sister, Petunia, from a county animal control. Petunia has since gone on to the Rainbow Bridge, so DaisyJane is learning to live life without her. DaisyJane is 16 years old and is tri-colored. She loves the warm house, plenty of food, and soft fluffy beds. She gets along fine with other dogs and with the humans she's met.

She says... "Hello everybody, yes you who are reading all about me! I may be 16 and deaf but I love my zoomies around the house and finish up with a jump into my warm fluffy bed. I'm learning about belly rubs, ooh, they're so good! When you have my attention, you're my best buddy. I get along with my dachshund siblings and I'm told I'm sweet tempered, whatever that means. When the weather is nice, foster Mom and I go for a wandering slow walk to check out the neighborhood if it isn't much farther than a couple of driveways down the block. I have a marvelous boowoo, deep and melodious. I go outside often to check on what's happening in the backyard, must keep them chipmunks and squirrels in their places. And at other times I do what us fabulous senior dogs love to do most, nap and dream in comfort, safe and loved. Would you consider sharing your home with me? What time I have left is being well spent. I'm protected, safe, warm, I have a full tummy and love. I'm not much trouble and I'm so darned lovely. Think about it, huh?

An adoption application is required but does not commit you to adoption. For the application and information about the adoption process, please visit  www.bhrg.org.

Yote is one and a half years old and about 15 lbs. He looks like a chihuahua/corgi mix. Tan with white. He is OK with other dogs; terrified of people. He should calm down with love, patience, CBD oil, someone experienced with quasi-feral animals.
He is neutered, has his shots, and is chipped. Very shy of people - taking CBD oil. He is a special socialization healing project. Foster home would be wonderful. These guys 'n gals can and will heal - given time to trust at their own speed and appropriate care.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

animal.description:
We do not ship dogs anywhere. You must come meet them in their foster home. 

What you don't see are the ones that are in various stages of being surrendered to us.

So if you want a Pyr  put your application in and start your end of the process even if you don't see a dog you want yet. more are coming.   

For Adoption Please go to 
http://www.nepyresq.org/page/adoption-process-guidelines-48.html



To SURRENDER please go to :


Step ONE is paperwork submitted.  We need to know about the dog so we can accurately place it in a foster home and a forever home. WE do not direct place from a surrender to an adopter.  The dogs are with us until  they can be vetted and we get to know them.

Step TWO is to go meet the dog and evaluate it for rehoming.  If he wants to eat our volunteer we can not take it in.

Step THREE is to contact the vet for their take on the dog and make sure we have all the medical records.  We can not take in a dog and bring it across state lines with our a current rabies shot and a negative heartworm test.

Step FOUR is to line up a FOSTER home for the dog.

Even if the dog is coming in from a shelter we still need to do steps ONE, TWO AND FOUR.  Luckily most shelters handle the medical paperwork and are ready to turn the dog over to us

animal.description:
Our loving, bonded babies Marley and Solo are looking for their forever home together. These two are incredibly friendly and loving, and they care deeply for each other, so they must stay together. They are searching for their special forever home.

Marley is an 8 year-old, female, long haired Mini Dachshund, and Solo is an 8 year-old male Chihuahua Mix. Solo is more outgoing -- in fact, one of the friendliest of chihuahuas! Marley is a bit more laid-back, but just as loving when she gets to know you, plus she is gorgeous.

One of their top hobbies is snuggling together in their soft bed. But they really excel at keeping their foster Mom’s lap warm! 

They get along with other dogs, and also with kids. At another foster’s house, they even ignored the cat. They’ve both been out on a leash and Solo, in particular, really enjoys it. Marley doesn’t want to be left behind, so she goes too!

They are house-trained as long as they stay on their routine, and are up to date on vaccinations, heartworm testing and have their identification chips.

Marley and Solo require a home with a fenced yard, and only local adopters in the Cincinnati, Columbus or Dayton region will be considered.

These guys are too good to pass up! They are like a little combined unit of sweetness!

If you have any questions regarding Marley and Solo, please email their foster mom at alicia.heidorn@gmail.com. If you would like to be considered to adopt them, please submit an Adoption Application Form through our website; www.PuppyPalsRescue.com. Thanks!

animal.description:
Breed Guess: Carolina Dog Mix 
Age: 2 years old 
Gender: Neutered Male
Children: NOT UNDER 10 years old
Cats: No
Dogs: Meet and Greet required
Housebroken: Unknown
Weight: 85 pounds
Adoption fee: $195.00

Leo is a sweet & active boy. He needs some time to warm up to people, but once he’s built a connection, he will reveal his sweet and goofy side. He is especially wary of men; at no fault of his own due to past experiences. It takes longer for him to adjust to men in the home so, he would prefer one without men if possible.

Leo would not do well in a home with small animals like rodents or cats as he has a high Prey drive. 

Obedience training is a must for Leo; he is still learning the world and is still figuring out what is and is not okay. He is not for a first time dog owner - he’ll need a gentle, but firm leader, due to both his breed as well as his past.  If you have interest in this boy, please do research on this breed prior as he will need an experienced owner. Leo doesn’t realize his size sometimes, but listens well to positive corrections. He LOVES food and will respond well to training with treats.

Leo is a gentleman on car rides, enjoys walks once he is comfortable, and is great at giving snuggles. Leo’s favorite thing to do is play in his kiddie pool, he enjoys sticking his whole mouth in to try and get the most water he possibly can. Leo will need a dog friend to tag along with or plenty of playtime and walks. A fenced in yard is also required, and no apartments for this big lug.

Leo will require a few meet and greets with any potential adopters due to his wariness towards people. Leo likes most other dogs; he would prefer a dog friend, but a meet and greet will be needed to make sure Leo is the perfect fit!

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description:
Winter aka Winnie

Located in western NE
Chihuahua mix 
5 years old
Good with other dogs
Good with cats
Good with kids with dog manners
NO MEN
House trained 
Kennel trained and knows a couple commands
Loves to cuddle 
Up to date on vaccines, will be spayed shortly
5lbs 

Winnie needs a new foster or foster to adopt home without a male.

This is Winnie and she's the sweetest little gal. Her story is an epically sad one.

We acquired Winnie after an epic mess of a situation regarding 2 adult Chihuahua mixes in Sterling CO. We were contacted and asked to take 2 adults, a male and female. We said we absolutely would and tried to coordinate pick up, however before we could drive to Sterling to get them picked up the owner gave them away. About 3 weeks later we were contacted because the woman she gave them to couldnt keep them, however now there was also a newborn puppy involved. We contacted the woman named Brenda and offered to take the family, she didnt want to give up the mother and pup. We agreed to take the male but we couldnt get there the same day and so Brenda dumped him. 

At this point we were very obviously concerned for the safety of the momma and pup with this Brenda woman however it was out of our hands. About a week later we got a message that Brenda had dumped the momma back with the original owner who couldnt keep her. At this point the puppy was 3 weeks old. It is 100% illegal to knowingly separate a momma and pup at this age, not to mention is inhumane and selfish. She said that the momma (Winnie) was not nursing the puppy and then began "attacking" the puppy which turned out to just be simply nipping at the puppy. 

When I got to Sterling to pick up the momma what I saw was beyond alarming. This dog was completely emaciated, she maybe had a body score of 1.5 and thats being generous. We scooped her up and went to speak to this Brenda woman who was refusing to give up the puppy. What she, to this day, refuses to understand is that momma had very little milk because SHE WASNT PROPERLY FED, AT ALL! We're sure she was nipping at the puppy because she was barely surviving herself. Sybil and another amazing volunteer, Jannette, went to speak with Brenda in hopes that she could be reasoned with to be a slightly decent human being, unfortunately that became clear that it wasnt possible. We did take Winnie in so she could see her pup and her desire to be with her pup was obvious and heartbreaking as the Brenda woman could have cared less. 

We took Winnie and got her settled into a foster where we began to evaluate her properly. We noticed very quickly that she had issues beyond being completely emaciated. Her legs and tail were deformed, and her skin was very dry and easily breaking and her coat was brittle and thin. On top of all of this she was stressed beyond belief and scared out of her mind, not to mention grieving for the puppy that was cruelly taken from her. 

We took her to the vet and honestly what we were told was pretty obvious. This dog had been neglected her entire life . She was likely born with bad luxating patellas and instead of taking her to the vet and having them corrected they just ignored the issue, at this point she has no knees and she has such significant scar tissue that she will never walk normally, and wheels may be in her future. There is no surgery at this point that can correct it because of the amount of scar tissue. Make no mistake she spent years in pain. Her tail was broken and never corrected. She has lacked proper nutrition for years. The good news is that she is safe now and has been in a fantastic foster home where she is loved beyond measure while we continue our plan of attack to get her as healthy as possible. Winnie is the product of 100% irresponsible animal ownership and neglect. We did contact law enforcement but AC couldnt do anything as the puppy wasnt in bad condition. This tiny princess didnt deserve how horrible her life has been, but she is so epically deserving of the fantastic future ahead of her. She will be available for adoption to a loving home as soon as she is healthy enough to be spayed which is close. In the mean time however we have found she doesn't like men. She does great with her foster momma and human foster sibling but not well with her foster dad. She is dog friendly but she does best with calm and passive dogs. We would love to find Winnie a new foster or foster to adopt home where she can continue to grow and recover without the company of an adult male.

If you can help this tiny lil lady let us know! 

 $200.00 Adoption Fee 
(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.) 

To Contact Us

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!My name was Robin Hood and I traveled the woods of WV with my Merry Men. One day while helping the poor and needy I got myself caught by this guy called a dog warden!! He asked for my identification well now that's just plain silly Robin Hood doesn't carry identification I mean I steal from the rich to feed the poor! He should have been able to tell that from the bone I just took from the overweight Rottweiler up the street that I was in the process of taking to the poor lab chained outside a few miles down the road sigggghhhhhhh. Anyhooo the man would not listen to reason and took me to this big noisy building filled with lots of dogs that really needed to learn to be quiet or if they were going to have choir practice needed to learn to sing! I was quietly planning my escape and hoping that my Merry Men were too when I began to feel a little under the weather I was picked up and taken to this human who poked and probed me. He was very lucky I am to much a gentleman to bite because I certainly didn't appreciate whatever it was he stuck up my butt or the piece of metal he poked me with not once but a few times!!! Finally when he was done messing with me I was taken by this really nice lady who took me out of the building that seemed to be a dog version of American Idol gone bad and to her house where I could get some sleep, get better and plan my next move. I was about to make a break for it when the lady decided to take me for a ride again BROTHER I thought if I am going back to where we were I might have to resort to acting ferocious! I found myself put in this thing with wheels and taken on a trip again with the singing choir YIKES! After what seemed like forever we arrived in a spot where I was handed off to another human who gave me smooshy kisses and seemed very glad to see me as if I was her long lost friend. She talked rather funny and seemed to think that after I took a quick restroom break we should get back in another thing on wheels and off we went again for another long trip. We then arrived at this home with a pretty young maiden with 4 paws. One look and I knew she would fall for me I mean all maidens do I'm Robin Hood for goodness sakes! Well to my surprise this maiden played hard to get and I have had to work very hard to win her over with my charms. Now I am pretty sure I am no where close to my old stomping grounds and I will have to find myself another group of Merry Men but I haven't quite given up on my old ways. With that being said I hate to tell on myself but someone is going to need a really good fence to keep me from "straying" so please unless you have a fence do not setup a date I just won't be able to help myself its like you humans with potatoe chips you just can't stop yourselves from eating the whole bag!!! Let's talk about snuggling, I have really learned to enjoy this thing called a couch and "human attention" I also am helping my human to stay fit by making sure he exercises each day with at least a 1.5 mile walk so if you are a slacker yeah its not gonna work. I am thinking that I will change my mission from stealing from the rich to feed the poor to walking my human so he eats no more!

Have a great night and feel free to fill out a date application and we will see if our "stars align"

Love Robin Hood or you can call me Robbie for short!
Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description: Hi my friends my name is Red and I have been here for some time. I am handsome and very cute. Most of the pictures you see are from when I was in a foster home. I was placed in a foster home  because I was adopted and not cared for. I came back to the shelter because of neglect and I looked so bad, so skinny. A foster home was found for me where I could be fed good food, given a soft bed and lots and lots of love. You can see my foster mom in one of my pictures. I was giving her a kiss. I am back at the shelter now waiting for my new family. I sure do wish they would come soon. I like it here but after having a great home with my foster family I know just how wonderful a loving, caring family can be. You can see I am use to being inside with people and the couch can be my favorite place with you. My adoption fee is $100 and this includes my shots, worming, micro chipping and neutering. To adopt me you have to email, call, Facebook or use this site to contact the shelter. This is different because of Covid. An application will be sent to you and then you will be given a date to come to the shelter to finish the adoption process for me and I will be ready for you to take me home...... I am Red

animal.description:
Gertie. Am Staff. 2.5 yo. 65lbs. Dogs. Kids.


This KWEEN of all of hearts was surrendered to a city shelter because the “owner” was done breeding her. He claimed she lived in the basement for a year because she would walk on leash. Fast forward being in our family... Gertie LOVES walks. LOVES humans. LOVES love. LOVES car rides. LOVES adventures. LOVES everything to do with life. Humans tried to break her but instead she grew her healing powers and is one of the greatest dogs to cross our path. She’s short, stout and incredibly soft and feminine. She’s a warrior and we absolutely love her. Looking for someone equally as special as she... that you? Last, did we say CUDDLE MONSTER?! That’s her. 

Animals can be viewed by appointment only. We ask that you review our adoption information AND fill out an adoption application prior to setting an appointment so we have all your information and you understand our adoption procedures - you can do so online here.     

Please feel free to email us or call us anytime for additional information on any of our animals - info@mcprescue.org or 312-388-3928. Our typical adoption fee varies based on the age of the dog at the time of rescue: Under the age of 1 years old is $500; 1-5 years old is $400; over the age of 5 is $300. Fees include vaccinations, microchip, deworming and other vetting as needed. Our adoption process includes an application, reference check and home visit.

animal.description: Fitzgerald is an amazing young man, but needs a very special home. He is protective of his people and must be muzzled when meeting new people or going out in public. He warms up quickly though. He really enjoys the company of boys age 7 to 15. They really bring him out of his shell. He loves other dogs, but does play very rough. He plays rough with people also, so small children are not recommended. He loves toys, especially a nice chew toy. He listens very well and loves to lounge around the house and follow his people around. To adopt Fitzgerald, please apply at www.hhfrescue.org. The adoption fee includes vaccinations, bordetella, deworming, rabies, spay/neuter, microchip, a lifetime registration of the microchip, and sales tax. If adopting a puppy, the rabies and spay/neuter will be done at the same time by our vet once they are 4 months old and billed to us. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.

He is looking to find a family to love. He doesn't like to put himself forward and has never been an 'in your face' kind of dog. He always wants to be a good boy. He likes to chase cats, so should go to a home with no cats. Admiral is dog selective and he will be fine being your only love.
Admiral will be a very loyal dog. He needs a privacy fenced yard where he can play and be safe as he is not good with other dogs. Rocky absolutely loves attention from his people. He's so smart and eager to learn and takes cues from his people so well. He also LOVES toys - tennis balls, his favorite stuffed alligator squeaky toy, you name it! Rocky enjoys walks and would be a great adventure buddy. Bonus, Rocky loves to fetch in a backyard or going for a daily jog. All Rocky wants to do is please his people. We know he'll be such a loyal companion if he's given the opportunity! The Orange Dot Crew (a volunteer advocacy group at Austin Animal Center) will be there every step of the way to make sure that Rocky is set up for success in his new home! animal.description:
Colorado bio, "Cher is a loveable momma dog who takes snuggling very seriously. Although she is very sweet to humans, due to her past she needs controlled formal introductions to other dogs and would prefer to be the only dog in the household! She's very well trained and knows sit, stay, lay down, leave it come and no. Cher is very smart and quick to pick up on new tricks. She is potty trained and great left home alone in no crate. Some of her favorite activities include fetch, tug of war, neighborhood walks and car rides. She loves any toy you give her! Cher is one with the outdoors and loves to hike, she is very good off-leash while camping. Cher is also a great running partner although she gets pretty pooped out at around 4 miles. Overall Cher looking for a nice home where she can snuggle up to someone who loves her."

 

Texas bio, "I AM NOT A DIVA! But I love to sing along with the radio!...

Hi - my name is Cher and I am happy to have arrived in Colorful Colorado and am looking to find my FOREVER family!

I am a beautiful 7-8 year old Boxer/Hound Mix. I weigh approximately 45lbs, am spayed, up-to-date on vaccinations, microchipped and recently completed my heartworm treatment, so I am now in tip-top shape to find a family that I can love (and so that I can be loved back).

I have had the unfortunate circumstance of having been found as a stray TWICE in Houston, Texas. Before my second incarceration, I had been "adopted" by a family. I was so excited to be there and loved the human child in my home. However, as the lives of the adults in the home became busier and more stressful, my home life became unstable. I was placed in a position of having to defend myself (and the child in my home). As my presence there became increasingly unappreciated, the adults decided to "give" me away to someone else...and the next thing I knew, I was back in doggie jail.

I am a sweet and spunky companion. I would love to go on walks with you or watch a movie on the couch. My intial introductions to other dogs have been uneventful, but my interest in felines might not make me the best match for a home with cats. Do to my energy level, a home with children over the age of 5-6 would probably be best. I have SO MUCH LOVE to give - won't you give me the chance to show you?"

Before you apply to adopt me, please note that home ownership is required. I have completed a formal breed evaluation to reside in the City/County of Denver without restriction, but may be subject to BSL restrictions in other areas (due to some of my physical characteristics).

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration

animal.description:
Hello friends! My name is Bullet. My shelter Aunties always tell me how good of a boy I am. I am calm, and came here from no fault of my own. I didn't come in the best shape though, I was kind of hungry and had really long nails. I have since gained some weight, and had a pedicure (but we're still working on making my nails pretty again). I came from a home with little children, and my family told the shelter that I really liked them. I am calm, but a ball or a treat can get me excited and ready to play! Come meet me and throw a ball and give me a treat, or 5! I'm guaranteed to like you, and win over your heart with my big beautiful eyes! My shelter family reminds me daily how sweet I am. I don't get to excited about other animals around me, but I would like to meet your current dogs before you adopt me just to make sure we like each other! 

Could you be my new forever family? I'd really like to find a family to love me as much as I can love them! Make an appointment to meet me, you wont regret it!

animal.description:
Ada is a beautiful German Shepherd, who loves playing with toys and in the water  She is extremely smart and is learning many new things. She is very friendly and has many human friends at Mackenzie's. Currently she is learning how to walk nicely on a lead and socializing with other dogs (going on walks & being introduced in play yards).  Cats & small dogs are not her thing, so she will need to have a home without them.  She did well on a few dog intros, but is dog selective.  She would do best in a laid back home, possibly as an only child.  She has also been introduced to kids, a 9 & 11 year old. She did good but since she doesn't realize her size we are suggesting kids over that age.
Ada came to Mackenzies from being picked up as a stray.  She had several medical things happening at that time.  Right now the main concern with Ada is she suffered in the past with bladder stones.  She is on a special diet, and has done very well since the inception of this diet.  She would need to have follow up veterinary checks, to make sure that all is consistently well with her.  She is a loving girl, and just needs the right home for her to thrive.  Please do not apply if you could not keep her UTD with annual veterinary checks, and a specific diet.   

I do require a special diet due to pancreatitis flareups.  

Birthday: 01/22/15

Meet-Your-Match Canine-ality color is: Orange- Goofball
For safety's sake, we are looking for homes with physical fenced in areas.
Please fill out our online adoption survey at www.mackenzies.info

animal.description:
Long-term foster.

Medical costs to date: $1,425.67

Please consider donating to Claire:

www.

paypal.me/scottiekingdomrescue

9-2-20: Claire has fully recovered from the surgery on her leg, but she still has coughing episodes after drinking water. The suggestion is for her to see a specialist and have an endoscopic exam of her esophagus, including a deeper inspection of her mouth. This specialized test is expensive and the results may or may not tell us what the issue is. Further, if there are results from the test, she may not be a candidate for surgery, especially considering her age. She has lived with this cough for many years and it is possible that it's best to just let it be, but we are still considering all options. Claire continues to have skin allergy issues that we are managing.

6-4-20: Claire returned to the vet for hospitalization today, as her surgery leg had become infected. After a night's stay with some intense treatment, she has returned home to continue her recovery.

6-1-20: Today, Claire underwent surgery to remove a tumor on her rear leg. The tumor, which was walnut-sized, will be sent out to a pathologist for analysis. Further, an extended dental exam and cleaning was performed, due to Claire's ongoing issue with coughing after drinking water. It is believed she has an opening near one of her canine teeth, but today's thorough exam and cleaning did not reveal the cause. We will be monitoring her when she returns home tonight.

Claire has now been to our vet and we have taken care of her current medical needs, such as flea dermatitis, ear infection, skin infection, intestinal parasites, vomiting, and diarrhea. This cutie pie was just groomed and her coat is growing back in where there was hair loss due to flea dermatitis. She has started her monthly flea and heartworm prevention, which should be continued throughout her life.

Claire LOVES attention and to be near her humans. She will happily sit in your lap during TV time and will give a gentle nudge if she isn't receiving all of the attention she craves! Claire is 11yo and quite the charmer.

- - - - - - -

This beautiful little girl has just arrived at our rescue and will be visiting our vet for all of her medical needs. Once we receive test results, we will update her bio. Claire is 11yo, and adorable!

Please consider donating to the high cost of medical care for Claire and for all of our senior dogs.

PayPal to Donate@scottiekingdom.com

Thank you!

All dogs adopted by Scottie Kingdom Rescue, Inc. have had a full medical exam by one of our licensed Veterinarians, which includes testing (and treatment, if necessary) for Heartworm disease, Lyme disease, Ehrlichia and Anaplasmosis, all necessary vaccinations, spay/neuter surgery, dental cleaning as necessary, microchipping, registration of the microchip, and any other medical needs each particular dog may need. Copies of all available medical records are transferred to you when the adoption is finalized.

We prefer to adopt to families with past Scottie, Westie, Terrier experience, but realize this isn't always possible. We do NOT ship our pets. If you have that special place in your heart, and in your home, for a Scottie (or any of our other available rescue dogs), please visit us in Dallas for an in person meet & greet session with our available dogs. If you have existing dogs, they should travel to Dallas with you, so we can be assured that they will be compatible with the new addition to your family.

Please contact us at
Rescue@scottiekingdom.com
to receive an Adoption Application or for more information on our Adoption process. Also, please take the time to visit our website
www.scottiekingdom.com
for additional information.

We sometimes receive several applications on the same dog. Our goal is to place the dog in the best home possible, based on his/her needs, personality and past history. Please note: Adoptions are not done on a first come, first served basis. Submitting an application does not guarantee the adoption of any dog. We are looking for the best available home for each of our rescue dogs.

Thank you for your understanding, and for considering adoption!

We are
not
supported by your tax dollars or public grants, rather, we rely on donations to help us continue our rescue work for animals that are in need.

Donations may be made via PayPal to email address:

Donate@scottiekingdom.com

or via USPS, to PO Box 551265 ~ Dallas, TX

75355

animal.description:
Meet Baker! This gentle Rottie mix might be the sweetest dog that has ever lived! Baker is approximately 2-3 years old and weighs 68 lbs.; he is gentle, loving and playful. Baker has severe hip dysplasia that will continue to worsen as he ages. While he gets around well now, it is likely that he will need to be put on a pain-management regimen later in life. Because of this condition, Baker is considered "special needs". Right now, Baker does just fine without the pain management medication; he is able to get up and down, run around with his favorite pal and lead a normal life. 

The fee to adopt Baker is $200.00; this includes neuter, deworming, vaccinations and a microchip. If you think Baker would make a good addition to your family, please visit our website, www.arfhouse.org and fill out an adoption application. 
**If adopted, Baker's adoptive family would take full financial responsibility of Baker's medical bills. 

**Please Note: Baker is currently located at our facility in Sherman, TX. If you are interested in meeting Baker, please fill out an adoption application on our website; if approved, we will contact you within 48 hours to set up a time to meet Baker.

animal.description:
BellaRose is a playful, affectionate Cairn terrier mix who is 3 years old and weighs 39 lbs. She was picked up as a stray, but we believe she may have been someone's pet because she has beautiful house manners and is friendly & obedient. She is good with adults (no young children please), knows basic commands, and responds well to corrections.  She is a typical scrappy little terrier, but she gets anxious when she sees other dogs and she has scars on her back that suggest she may have been attacked by another dog in the past.  She has a high prey drive so she's looking for an only dog home with no cats or possibly a home with larger, well balanced dogs that she could coexist with after slow introductions.  She is nervous & reactive on walks and has received professional training to address this behavior, but she needs a strong leader who will continue working with her to build trust so she feels safe.  She would enjoy a fully fenced yard with privacy fencing (preferred height of 6 ft) because this little dynamo will clear a 5 ft chain link fence in no time flat and cannot be trusted to stay behind the fence if other dogs are walking past her yard!  Bella is housebroken, crate trained, spayed, fully vaccinated and microchipped.

For more information about BellaRose, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt sweet BellaRose, please submit an adoption application for her at http://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Say hello to gorgeous Gambit! He joined us last year from a state police cruelty case but is not letting that get him down. Instead, he’s looking forward to a bright future and someone special to share it with. Gambit has spent several months learning how to just be a dog and has blossomed into a wonderful, and sometimes quirky, middle-age boy (past the naughty puppy stage!). He’s estimated to be about 7 years old, but you would never know it! He has lots of great energy and would love someone active to explore the world with. Some of his favorite things are long walks, a soft place to nap, smelly treats, his crate, trying to break the world record of ripping stuffing out of a toy, and his foster mom. Actually, Gambit loves women in general. Okay, we’ll be honest, he’s a full fledged “ladies man”. The good news is, he’s a stayer, not a player! As for men, he can be nervous around them. This is something he is working on and any men in his life will need to be patient and understanding. Of course, he’d be totally cool with having a new lady all to himself too! 

Gambit’s forever home would be kid and kitty free. He does love to play with his canine foster brother and would welcome a doggie sibling but will need a family committed to taking things slow. This hunk didn’t get the right kind of socialization when he was younger, so this is all new to him! He would also be perfectly content to be your one and only. Most importantly, he needs structure, a good leader, and a family committed to helping him live his very best life. 

If you’re fun-loving, active, and looking for a hunky blond to join you on life’s adventures, Gambit just might be the one for you!

To meet Gambit, please visit our website, www.pittieslovepeace.com, to submit an adoption application. Gambit is neutered, microchipped and vaccinated. His adoption fee is $250.00 and includes doggie kisses and a lifetime of LOVE.

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing a predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.
