animal.description:
Are you looking for a running buddy? Hiking buddy? Adventure partner? Well look no further- Zeus is your guy! Zeus is a young bundle of fun! He’s happiest while being active with his human and furry friends. Zeus was very loved the first year of his life but is looking for a home better suited for getting his puppy energy out. He needs a large, fenced yard to run around and play. A tired Zeus is a good Zeus :) Like most Pyrs, Zeus can have selective hearing and can exhibit some resource guarding tendencies. He has work to do on his manners when greeting new humans and other dogs on a leash, but Zeus is highly food motivated and a delicious treat seems to help him remember his obedience commands very quickly. He is house broken, crate-trained and walks well on a leash (unless other dogs are nearby). Zeus plays well with canine pals after proper introductions and would benefit from a doggy sibling to play with in his yard! He is a very good boy - handsome, smart and a quick learner! If you’re the active family Zeus is looking for, apply today!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Stryker is a beautiful black female greyhound that turned 2 years old on 2/18/2020 and has been with our adoption program since 8/14/2019. 

Stryker came from a loving farm in Abilene, KS where she was bred for racing but was retired without being trained to race due to her shy and timid nature. It does take a while to earn her trust, but she has made some great progress in her foster home! 

Stryker is a very reserved and easily startled greyhound that would do best in a home without children. She will need a special home with a patient person. She does better with a structured routine and needs time to adjust to any changes. She will also need interaction with other dogs and greyhounds(play dates).

She is very food motivated when it comes to training but she is unsure walking on a leash and will require a house with a fenced yard for her to play in. She requires a harness anytime you leave the house because she will try to back out of a collar and if that happens, she's so fast that you'll never be able to catch her.

Once you have earned her trust, she is a very playful, funny girl who loves squeaky toys, naps and treats. She gets along beautifully with the cats in her foster home and loves playing with her Greyhound foster siblings.

animal.description:
Josie is an energetic one year old blackmouth cur mix. She is a loyal girl who had a rough start in life. Josie sustained some kind of injury to her spine as a puppy and could not use her back legs. She was rescued from a high kill shelter in Houston and put into foster for some physical rehab and lots of love.
Josie has been with us for a while and can now use her legs most of the time to hop around the yard with other dogs. She loves to run and she is fast! Josie needs a nice big backyard to run to her hearts content in and expend all her energy. When she is tired she does drag a bit, but when she catches her second wind she pops back up. She does best on a harness rather than a neck collar but she will tolerate a gentle slip lead.
Due to nerve damage Josie is incontinent. With frequent potty breaks outside, spending time on non-carpeted flooring, and a good mop this can be managed. A vet tech or someone with a background in animal care would be an amazing match for her.
Josie is still a big puppy, so she likes to chew. Very hefty chew toys are best for her. She can be mouthy when excited and could possibly knock over small children, so adults or older children are best for her new family. Josie would be happy being by your side all day however she is used to being in a crate for nap time and quiet moments. Fuzzy blankets rather than stuffing filled dog beds are best in her crate, though with supervision she loves relaxing in a nice big dog bed outside the crate during family time.
She is used to being around dogs and cats with no issues other than liking to be up in their business. She loves friends.

animal.description:
Lacie is an energetic Aussie, born January 2019. Because she has so much energy and is so smart, she needs a very special owner who is able to meet and challenge her mental and physical needs. She is a sweet dog who takes time to warm up to people, especially men. Once she gets comfortable with people, she will snuggle, shower them with kisses, and give them lots of attention. She can be nervous in large social settings and prefers to be with her chosen people and animals. She loves to go on hikes, watch Netflix and cuddle with her people. Her perfect home will be with a very patient owner who will help Lacie excel in life. Her perfect home will be with a very patient owner who will provide daily activities that will meet Lacie's physical and mental needs so that she will excel in life. 

Lacie would do well as an only pet or a home with a younger playful dog, as she loves to play. Cats would not be a good idea as she thinks they are fun to chase. 

Due to Lacie being a fearful/reactive dog she will not be adopted to a home located in an apartment, a home that does not have a fence, a home with kids of any age, or a home with cats. 
Lacie needs a calm home with one or two people, preferably that understand herding dogs, and understand and/or have experience with dogs who have fear/reactive issues. These requirements are to ensure Lacie and her new family have the best and long-term life together.

The suggested adoption donation for Lacie is $400 We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet.

The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
On November 11, 2018, Simon and Travis came into our world. Two precious little boys that were part of a 22 dog, court ordered seizure. Three rescues were involved, and vets were on standby, waiting for the dogs to be captured and delivered. When we arrived at the location , there were 22 numbered collars on a table , cadaver bags available. As the dogs are caught, they are crated in the closest vehicle. Once the vehicle is full it heads to the clinic. The dogs were in serious condition. Purebreds, mixes, pregnant, you name it. Whatever dog(s) end up in your vehicle, you take. After being released from the vet,the boys arrived at Lucies and were put in major quarantine for a month. We noticed that they seemed to have a fondness for each other. Carrying on little conversations through the fence. They were overjoyed when we put them into a yard together. We also noticed that they were similar in a number of ways. They insist on eating and sleeping together, although they curse each other in their very own language while they do it. We have no doubt that they are brothers. In all the chaos that day, Simon and Travis were loaded into Lucies vehicles. Luck??? Please pardon the length of this post, we can’t split them up. Last month they received a clean bill of health and are ready for adoption. Please share their story, there has to be someone that needs some laughter and love in their lives.
Simon and Travis are crate and leash trained. They will follow off lead. Kid and K9 friendly. Approximately 6 years old and weighing about 35-40 pounds. Thanks y’all ??!

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
Bernie is a sweet older gentleman who is looking for a home with someone dedicated to making his remaining years comfortable and easy. He is low on the energy scale and likes to sleep on soft comfortable things. 

He has not had the best care all these years but has a great capacity for forgiveness. He is happy to have another day of this great life. Bernie recently finished heartworm treatment. 

Bernie barks at people who approach his yard but he is very easy going when meeting new people, He is an enthusiastic eater. In general, he likes to check out what is happening and then go back to bed. He enjoys yard time, and seeing who is outside, but a little bit of a good thing is just fine. He prefers to be with people and watching things from the dog bed. He is a little scared in storms and it's extra nice to be with his person when the sky is making noise.

Bernie was neutered prior to his arrival and is microchipped and up to date on all his shots. He is an inside dog who needs a fenced yard. 

He is likely 10-11 years old and weighs about 52 pounds, He had a dog friend that he came here with who recently passed away (internal bleeding, likely cancer) and we have not introduced Bernie to anyone new.  Anyone adopting Bernie does so with the understanding that he may have several good years ahead but he will have age-related issues and expenses. We are looking for a compassionate soul who has experience with senior dogs and wants nothing more than to enjoy slow life with Bernie. We have had him in the cat building and he did not notice the cats.

animal.special_needs_notes:
Bernie is a senior and is a special needs dog. He will need a home where he can enjoy his senior years. He does not like to be locked inside a house and has anxiety being confined in spaces. He has indoor/outdoor access at our house and this works well for Bernie. 

He has access to a secure yard and this seems to calm him. He won't come outside if there are lots of people outside or unfamiliar people. He will watch from the doorway. 

Bernie lived most of his life with his brother Bruce, who died recently of cancer. We think this makes Bernie more dependent on the people he knows and that he doesn't like to be alone. Bernie and his brother came into rescue after a life of neglect and abuse. Bernie deserves a home where he can be himself and be around people who love him.

It will take a very special and patient home to accommodate Bernie's needs. Adopter must have the means and experience in dealing with an older dog who is not a "dog park" dog. Bernie's experience with other dogs here has been limited, he seems to be selective. We have not found him a friend to live with yet b/c of the variety of recent transitions for him. 

If you are interested in Bernie, please fill out a pre-adoption application that can be found on our website or on the page that accompanies this description. This is the best way to start the conversation about adopting Bernie.

animal.description:
We are scheduling meet-and-greets BY APPOINTMENT ONLY for pre-screened applicants. Our shelter is closed to the general public to help reduce the spread of the COVID-19 virus.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN AN ANIMAL, please submit an application form: https://www.newwestcity.ca/services/animal-services/animal-shelter

We need your help finding Ben G's perfect home! He has been at the shelter for a year now.

Ben G is an energetic 8 year old Rottweiler who came to our shelter with another dog, Boston. The boys were living in a van in sub-zero temperatures, so our Animal Services Officers removed them. The owner had fallen on hard times and was not able to claim them.

Ben G is a silly, playful boy. He loves to play with toys and run around the yard. He enjoys his walks out in the neighbourhood, and loves a good sniff around. We are looking for a pet-free home for Ben G. He is not an off-leash dog park candidate, so we want to see him in a home where he has a fully fenced yard to play in. Condos and townhouses are not suitable.

Like many Rottweilers, some strangers make Ben G nervous. He is great at communicating if he is not comfortable, and will try to avoid if possible. For this reason, we are looking for an adult-only home without a lot of comings-and-goings. But once you're friends, get ready for endless bum-scratch-requests! He'll back his booty right up to you.

Ben G is very food-motivated which makes training easy. He can be grabby and pushy when treats are present but we have not seen any food/resource-guarding behaviour.

In September, we noticed that Ben G was a bit sore after walks and had some weakness in his hindquarters. We had full x-rays done of his knees, hips, and spine. He appears to have an old injury to one of his knees, but unfortunately, his lower spine has some spots that have fused together. This means he will need to be on anti-inflammatory and pain relief medication for the rest of his life.  He is on a daily medication, Galliprant, to help with his mobility, and it has done wonders! He is much more comfortable now.

If you think Ben G is a perfect fit for you, please submit an adoption application, found at https://www.newwestcity.ca/.../animal.../animal-shelter
